ory:Products introduced in 2001]]\n[[Category:Products and services discontinued in 2014]]\n[[Category:Portable media players]]\n[[Category:ITunes]]\n[[Category:Discontinued products]]\n", "name_user": "NathanOrWhatever", "label": "safe", "comment": "I fixed a minor grammatical error", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/IPod_Classic"}
{"title_page": "Teleprompter", "text_new": "{{for|the racehorse|Teleprompter (horse)}}\n{{redirect|TelePrompTer|the media company|TelePrompTer Corporation}}\n[[File:Teleprompter schematic.svg|thumb|300px|Schematic representation: (1)&nbsp;Video camera; (2)&nbsp;Shroud; (3)&nbsp;Video monitor; (4)&nbsp;Clear glass or beam splitter; (5)&nbsp;Image from subject; (6)&nbsp;Image from video monitor]]\n\nA '''teleprompter''' is a [[display device]] that prompts the person speaking with an [[Electronics|electronic]] visual [[Character (computer)|text]] of a [[Public speaking|speech]] or [[Screenplay|script]]. Using a teleprompter is similar to using [[cue cards]]. The screen is in front of, and usually below, the [[Camera lens|lens]] of a [[professional video camera]], and the words on the screen are reflected to the eyes of the [[Television presenter|presenter]] using a sheet of clear glass or a specially prepared [[beam splitter]]. Light from the [[performer]] passes through the front side of the glass into the lens, while a shroud surrounding the lens and the back side of the glass prevents unwanted light from entering the lens. Mechanically this works in a very similar way to the \"[[Pepper's Ghost]]\" illusion from classic theatre \u2013 an image viewable from one angle but not another \u2013 and the concept may have similar origins.\n\nBecause the speaker does not need to look down to consult written notes, the teleprompter creates the illusion that the speaker has [[Memorization|memorized]] the speech or is speaking spontaneously, looking directly into the camera lens. Cue cards, on the other hand, are always placed away from the lens axis, making the speaker look at a point beside the camera, which leaves an impression of distraction.\n\nThe technology has continued to develop. From the first mechanical paper roll teleprompters used by television presenters and speakers at U.S. political conventions in 1952;<ref name=Smithsonian>{{cite web|url=https://www.smithsonianmag.com/history/a-brief-history-of-the-teleprompter-88039053/|title=A Brief History of the Teleprompter (click on fourth photo image box for description and clearer view)|author=Stromberg, Joseph|date=22 October 2012|accessdate=3 June 2018}}</ref> to dual glass teleprompters used by TV presenters and for U.S. conventions in 1964;<ref name=Getty>{{cite web|url=https://www.gettyimages.co.uk/album/kiss-and-teleprompter-a-look-back-at--ZSKiLqlWBUaxLQhi1gvBTg#attorney-general-robert-kennedy-smiling-but-with-tears-in-his-eyes-picture-id515489640|title=Kiss and Teleprompter|work=Getty Images|accessdate=3 June 2018}}</ref> to the computer-based rolls of 1982 and the four-prompter system for U.S. conventions which added a large off-stage confidence monitor and inset lectern monitor in 1996;<ref name=DFP>{{cite web|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/99340726/|title=Speakers send a strong message|work=Detroit Free Press (Detroit, Michigan)|date=August 27, 1996|accessdate=3 June 2018}}</ref> to the replacement of glass teleprompters at U.K. political conferences by several large off-stage confidence monitors in 2006;.<ref name=Guardian>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2008/sep/18/liberaldemocrats.libdemconference|title=Bog standard search for Elysium|work=[[The Guardian]]|author=Hoggart, Simon|date=18 September 2008|accessdate=3 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe word ''TelePrompTer'', with [[CamelCase|internal capitalization]], originated as a [[trade name]] used by the TelePrompTer Company, which first developed the device in the 1950s; it is now a [[genericized trademark]]. [[Autocue]], a [[United Kingdom]] manufacturer of teleprompters, also finds its trademark used in a generic fashion in [[Commonwealth of Nations|Commonwealth]] countries and some European countries.\n\n==History==\n[[File:LBJ Civil Rights Act crowd.jpg|right|thumb|U.S. President [[Lyndon B. Johnson]] uses a teleprompter while announcing the [[Civil Rights Act of 1964]].]]\nThe [[TelePrompTer Corporation]] was founded in the 1950s by [[Fred Barton, Jr.]], [[Hubert Schlafly]] and [[Irving Berlin Kahn]]. Barton was an [[actor]] who suggested the [[concept]] of the teleprompter as a means of assisting [[television]] performers who had to memorize large amounts of material in a short time.<ref>{{Cite book\n| publisher = The Difference\n| isbn = 0-9767761-0-3\n| last = Brown\n| first = Laurie\n| title = The Teleprompter Manual\n| date = 2005-12-28\n}}</ref>\nSchlafly built the first teleprompter in 1950. It was simply a mechanical device, operated by a hidden technician, located near the camera.<ref>Engineers' Device Eased Speechmakers' Minds, Wall Street Journal, April 26, 2011, p.A6</ref> The script, in inch-high letters, was printed by a special electric typewriter on a paper scroll, which was advanced as the performer read, and the machines rented for the then-considerable sum of $30 per hour.<ref>\"TV's Cost-Cutting Gadets,\" Sponsor, 22 September 1952, 36. [http://americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Sponsor-Magazine/1952/Sponsor-1952-09-2.pdf Green Bay-de Pere Telephone Directory {{!}} Even Our Phone Number Tells Our Story... ADAMS 1 \u2192 TV gadgets that save money for sponsors]</ref> In 1952 former President [[Herbert Hoover]] used a Schlafly-designed speech teleprompter to address the [[1952 Republican National Convention]] in [[Chicago, Illinois|Chicago]]. U.S. Governor [[Paul A. Dever]] spoke at the [[1952 Democratic National Convention]], also held in Chicago, using a mechanical-roll teleprompter on a long pole held by a TV technician in the convention audience, while the [[1952 Republican National Convention]] used a smaller teleprompter placed in front of the speaker's rostrum.<ref name=Smithsonian/> Mechanical prompters were still being used as late as 1992, as was the case with ''[[The Tonight Show Starring Johnny Carson]]''.{{citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\nOn January 4, 1954,<ref>\"Ike Uses Pair of Teleprompters.\" Cleveland Plain Dealer, January 6, 1954, p. 13.</ref> [[Dwight Eisenhower]] was the first President to use a teleprompter for a State of the Union address.<ref>[http://www.smithsonianmag.com/history-archaeology/A-Brief-History-of-the-Teleprompter-175411341.html A Brief History of the Teleprompter]</ref>\n\n[[Jess Oppenheimer]], who created ''[[I Love Lucy]]'' and served for its first five years as its producer and head writer, developed the first \"in-the-lens\" prompter<ref name=\"Oppenheimer\">Laughs, [https://books.google.com/books?id=7fW-rGDmGxIC&pg=PA204 Luck...and Lucy: How I Came to Create the Most Popular Sitcom of All Time, by Jess Oppenheimer with Gregg Oppenheimer], pp. 204-205.</ref> and was awarded U.S. patents<ref>{{cite patent|US|2883902}}</ref><ref>{{cite patent|US|2926559}}</ref> for its creation. This system uses a mirror to reflect a script onto a piece of glass placed in front of the camera lens, thus allowing the reader to look directly into the camera. First used by [[Lucille Ball]] and [[Desi Arnaz]] in 1953<ref name=\"Oppenheimer\"/> to read commercials on-camera, it soon became a staple of [[television news]] and is the primary system used with prompters today.\n\nThe first [[personal computer]]-based teleprompter, Compu=Prompt appeared in 1982. It was invented and marketed by Courtney M. Goodin and Laurence B. Abrams in Los Angeles, California. The custom software and specially-redesigned camera hardware ran on the Atari 800 Personal Computer, which featured smooth hardware-assisted scrolling. Their company later became ProPrompt, Inc., which is still providing teleprompting services over 32 years later. Other paper-based teleprompting companies Electronic Script Prompting, QTV and Telescript followed suit and developed their own software several years later, when computers with enough graphics power to provide the smooth scrolling text became available. In January 2010 Compu=Prompt received a Technology and Engineering Emmy Award for \"Pioneering Development in Electronic Prompting\".\n\n==Etymology==\n[[File:teleprompter.jpg|thumb|A teleprompter displaying text]]{{Unreferenced section|date=June 2017}}\n\nThe word \"TelePrompTer\", with [[CamelCase|internal capitalization]], originated as a [[trade name]] used by the TelePrompTer Company, which first developed the device in the 1950s. The word \"teleprompter\", with no capitalization, has become a [[genericized trademark]], because it is used to refer to similar systems manufactured by many different companies. The [[United States Patent Office]] does not have any live trademarks registered for the word ''teleprompter'', but this does not rule out the possibility of a company enforcing the trademark without registering it. Some other common terms for this type of device are:\n* [[Autocue]] or Autoscript (the trademark of Autocue Group Ltd, most commonly used in [[Commonwealth of Nations|Commonwealth]] countries; Autoscript is used to brand the devices in the United States)\n* cueing device\n* electronic speech notes\n* idiot board (slang)\n* prompter\n\n==Modern design==\n\n===Television===\n[[File:Teleprompter in use.jpg|thumb|right|230px|Teleprompter in use]]\n\nModern teleprompters for [[news program]]s consist of a [[personal computer]], connected to [[video monitor]]s on each [[professional video camera]]. In certain systems, the PC connects to a separate display device to offer greater flexibility in setup, distances and cabling. The monitors are often black-and-white and have the scanning reversed to compensate for the reflection of the [[mirror]]. A [[peripheral device]] attached has a knob that can be turned to speed up, slow down, or even reverse the scrolling of the text. The text is usually displayed in white letters on a black background for the best readability, while cues are in inverse video ([[light-on-dark color scheme|black on white]]). Difficult words (mainly international names) are spelled out [[phonetic]]ally,<ref>[http://uk.reuters.com/article/idUKN2540350420070926 Reuters: When words get in the way, Bush goes phonetic]</ref> as are other particulars like \"Nine-eleven\" (to specify that the event [[September 11 attacks|9/11]] should not be [[pronunciation|pronounced]] \"[[9-1-1|nine-one-one]]\", for example).\n\nWith the development of inexpensive teleprompter [[software application]]s as well as free Web-based teleprompter applets, many different disciplines are now using teleprompters to help them deliver sermons, deliver speeches, and to create quality audio recordings. Unlike their more advanced counterparts, these entry level products work on desktop computers, laptop computers, and even tablet computers to enable the speaker to control the rate and flow of their speech. They are also used by many different organizations and schools to deliver prewritten information by relative novices. They are usually called \"personal teleprompters.\"\n\n===Presidential (or glass) teleprompters===\n[[File:SOU2007.jpg|thumb|right|230px|[[George W. Bush]] next to two glass teleprompters. They can be seen more clearly by clicking on this image and the one below.]]\n[[File:Joe Biden 2008 DNC (1).jpg|thumb|right|230px|[[Joe Biden]] flanked by two glass teleprompters. The two teleprompter monitors are embedded in the floor of the podium.]]\n\nGlass teleprompters were first used at the [[1956 Democratic National Convention]]. The inventor of the teleprompter, Hubert Schlafly, explained that he wanted to create a less obtrusive teleprompting system than the ones used at the time. He said, \"We developed a 'one way mirror' device we called the ''Speech View'' system... The prompter, hidden in the base, reflected the text on the glass to the speaker while the audience looked through the glass without being aware of the text. Two such prompters, one on the right and one on the left of the speaker allowed him to switch from one to the other and appear to address the entire audience\".<ref name=TTM>Laurie Brown, ''The Teleprompter Manual'' (Pleasant Ridge, Michigan: The Difference Press, 2006), pp. 5\u20136. {{ISBN|0-9767761-0-3}}.</ref>\n\nSchlafly's company then created a speaker's lectern that included two synchronized glass teleprompters and a range of technological innovations including air conditioning and an adjustable-height speaker's platform. The success of the system led the company to develop a new model for use on TV cameras, with the glass placed directly in front of the lens. The camera \"looked through the glass; the performer looked directly at the TV audience and was able to read the text word for word. This device now has worldwide use\".<ref name=TTM/>\n\nTypically, a screen on either side of the speaker shows mirrored text from upward-facing floor monitors at the base of a stand supporting a [[one-way mirror]] at the top, angled down towards the screen. The speaker sees the text on the screen reflected in the mirror, while the audience sees what looks like a sheet of tinted glass on each side of the speaker.\n\nSchlafly's glass teleprompters were also used for the [[1956 Republican National Convention]], and at both parties' conventions from then on. In 1964, glass teleprompters were used by [[Robert F. Kennedy]], at the time the [[United States Attorney General|U.S. Attorney General]], who served in both the [[Presidency of John F. Kennedy|Kennedy]] and early [[Presidency of Lyndon B. Johnson|Johnson]] Administrations (1961-1964), to deliver his convention speech.<ref name=Getty/>\n\n===Confidence monitors===\n[[File:2012 DNC day 2 (7958010012).jpg|thumb|right|230px|(A) The first three teleprompters: A monitor screen partly-embedded in the lectern's desk top displays the scrolling text of the speech in synchrony with two screens embedded in the podium floor. They are on either side of the speaker, reflected by the angled glass teleprompters above them. Click this image and the ones below to see the four-teleprompter system more clearly.]]\n[[File:2012 DNC day 3 Brian Schweitzer (7959825568).jpg|thumb|right|230px|(B) The fourth teleprompter: A large confidence monitor displays the scrolling text of the speech immediately below the lenses of the broadcast TV cameras, several metres/feet away from the speaker.]]\n[[File:Barack_Obama_Denver_Speech_2008.jpg|thumb|right|230px|(C) The above-described four-teleprompter set-up in use at the [[2008 Democratic National Convention]] in [[Denver]], [[Colorado]], USA (the large confidence monitor under the TV cameras is near the bottom far right of this frame).]]\n\nIn 1996, for the first time, speakers at the ''[[1996 Democratic National Convention|Democratic National Convention]]'', held at the [[United Center]] in [[Chicago]], Illinois, used a four-teleprompter system: as can be seen at another convention in image (A) on the right, the first three prompters are placed to the left, right and in front of the speaker, the latter embedded within the speaker's [[lectern]], enabling the speaker to look down at the lectern without losing his/her place in the text of the speech; while in image (B) below it, the fourth prompter is a large confidence monitor located immediately below the lenses of the TV broadcast cameras, at a distance of several metres/yards from the speaker.\n\nThis modification to the traditional two-teleprompter set-up continues to be in use at both the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] and [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] parties' national conventions: the two glass teleprompters on either side of the speaker's lectern create the illusion that the speaker is looking directly at the audience in the hall, the monitor embedded in the lectern, together with the fourth, much larger teleprompter screen, known as a 'confidence monitor', placed immediately below the broadcast TV cameras which are located some distance away from the convention stage on a specially-constructed broadcasting gantry. This placement of the center prompter creates the illusion that the speaker is periodically looking straight into the camera lens, and thereby appears to directly address the TV audience watching the televised Convention coverage.<ref name=DFP/>\n\nIn 2006, speakers at the ''[[Liberal Democrat Federal Conference]]'', held at the [[Brighton Centre]] in [[Brighton]], UK, also used a three-screen system (but this time consisting entirely of large off-stage confidence monitors mounted on poles \u2014 which are often described outside [[North America]], together with glass teleprompters, as \"[[autocue]]s\"), where the skill required for those using it, according to the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]]' former leader, [[Menzies Campbell]] (2006\u20142008), is to move their gaze seamlessly from one screen to the other: left, centre (near the broadcast TV cameras), right and then back again.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=W38dAwAAQBAJ&pg=PT248&lpg=PT248&dq=%22menzies+campbell+my+autobiography%22+autocues&source=bl&ots=tChf4KOF4O&sig=MeKqS7d9_OS3htvVbfUATPI5zG0&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiSksjY8aTbAhXlCMAKHRMaBR8Q6AEIJzAA#v=onepage&q=%22menzies%20campbell%20my%20autobiography%22%20autocues&f=false|title=Menzies Campbell: My Autobiography|author=Campbell, Menzies|work=Hachette Books, London|date=2014|accessdate=27 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nAs well as helping the speaker to appear to sometimes directly address the TV audience during his/her speech, this system also allows the speaker \u2014 in another case cited, the party's then-new leader, [[Nick Clegg]] (2008\u20142015) \u2014 to abandon the podium lectern and roam the stage, speaking with apparent spontaneity but in fact constantly assisted by three large autocue screens placed throughout the conference hall.<ref name=Guardian/> Ironically, this use of the system was adopted by Clegg to counter the oratorical success of another party leader, [[David Cameron]] (later to become British Prime Minister), who bestrode stages while speaking seemingly off-the-cuff, having memorized key parts of his speech.<ref name=Atkinson>{{cite web|url=http://maxatkinson.blogspot.co.uk/2009/09/cleggs-conference-speech-definitely-ok.html|title=Clegg\u2019s conference speech: 'definitely OK, absolutely fine, without any doubt not bad'|author=Atkinson, Max|date=24 September 2009|accessdate=27 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nThis multiple use of off-stage confidence monitors also dispenses with the need for glass teleprompters to be present on the conference stage, thereby reducing \"stage clutter\", and removes the inevitable restrictions on the speaker's movement and field of vision imposed by on-stage glass prompters. The disadvantage of such a system is that the provision of \"giant teleprompters\" becomes essential to maintaining the illusion of speaking with apparent spontaneity.<ref name=Atkinson/>\n\n'''<big>Teleprompters in India</big>'''\n[[Harish Bhimani]], a National Awardee in Voiceovers pioneered the age of teleprompters in India, was quoted as saying:\n\n<blockquote>\nThe Teleprompter has been on my wish list since way back in 1978 when I went to the US on a holiday. During this visit, a trip to the news-room of a TV channel was my top priority \u2013 certainly more than a visit to the Statue of Liberty! Being an established newscaster on TV back in India, I was very keen to see how the broadcasting fraternity functioned in the most advanced country in the world.\n\nThe first thing that struck him was the level of professionalism in their approach.\n\nIn a nut-shell, if you are expected to give a top-notch performance, you also received the best facilities to make such a performance possible. That is when I first saw a TELEPROMPTER!\n\nIt was a dream! No shuffling of haphazardly scribbled news items on sheets of paper! A visibly relaxed expression, with an added ease in impromptu asides! I came back to Mumbai and the daily grind, resigned to the fact that our TV was not yet ready to pamper us 'over-paid' newscasters with a teleprompter.\n</blockquote>\n\nBut the teleprompter stayed with him and he managed to get the first privately owned teleprompter to India in 1992. He then assembled the most suitable model for the then prevailing Indian conditions \u2013 including the [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=n0lzuqlTXa8 multi-lingual milieu], thus pioneering tele prompting in India.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Cue card]]\n* A similar device called an interrotron is often used by filmmaker [[Errol Morris]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Nobile, Jr |first1=Phil |title=The Interrotron: How Errol Morris Changed The Way Documentaries Watch Us |url=https://birthmoviesdeath.com/2017/07/07/the-interrotron-how-errol-morris-changed-the-way-documentaries-watch-us |website=Birth.Movies.Death. |language=en |date=7 July 2017}}</ref> Instead of text, a live image of the interviewer (or the interviewee) is displayed, allowing both conversation partners to look straight at the camera.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Pavlus |first1=John |title=Errol Morris\u2019s Secret Weapon for Unsettling Interviews: The Interrotron |url=https://www.fastcompany.com/1663105/errol-morriss-secret-weapon-for-unsettling-interviews-the-interrotron |website=Fast Company |date=30 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Teleprompters}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120107211123/http://www.emmyonline.tv/mediacenter/tech_2k9_winners.html 2010 Engineering & Technology Emmy Awards for Prompting]\n\n[[Category:American inventions]]\n[[Category:Film and video technology]]\n[[Category:Television technology]]\n[[Category:Television terminology]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the racehorse|Teleprompter (horse)}}\n{{redirect|TelePrompTer|the media company|TelePrompTer Corporation}}\n[[File:Teleprompter schematic.svg|thumb|300px|Schematic representation: (1)&nbsp;Video camera; (2)&nbsp;Shroud; (3)&nbsp;Video monitor; (4)&nbsp;Clear glass or beam splitter; (5)&nbsp;Image from subject; (6)&nbsp;Image from video monitor]]\n\nA '''teleprompter''' is a [[display device]] that prompts the person speaking with an [[Electronics|electronic]] visual [[Character (computer)|text]] of a [[Public speaking|speech]] or [[Screenplay|script]]. Using a teleprompter is similar to using [[cue cards]]. The screen is in front of, and usually below, the [[Camera lens|lens]] of a [[professional video camera]], and the words on the screen are reflected to the eyes of the [[Television presenter|presenter]] using a sheet of clear glass or a specially prepared [[beam splitter]]. Light from the [[performer]] passes through the front side of the glass into the lens, while a shroud surrounding the lens and the back side of the glass prevents unwanted light from entering the lens. Mechanically this works in a very similar way to the \"[[Pepper's Ghost]]\" illusion from classic theatre \u2013 an image viewable from one angle but not another \u2013 and the concept may have similar origins.\n\nBecause the speaker does not need to look down to consult written notes, the teleprompter creates the illusion that the speaker has [[Memorization|memorized]] the speech or is speaking spontaneously, looking directly into the camera lens. Cue cards, on the other hand, are always placed away from the lens axis, making the speaker look at a point beside the camera, which leaves an impression of distraction.\n\nThe technology has continued to develop. From the first mechanical paper roll teleprompters used by television presenters and speakers at U.S. political conventions in 1952;<ref name=Smithsonian>{{cite web|url=https://www.smithsonianmag.com/history/a-brief-history-of-the-teleprompter-88039053/|title=A Brief History of the Teleprompter (click on fourth photo image box for description and clearer view)|author=Stromberg, Joseph|date=22 October 2012|accessdate=3 June 2018}}</ref> to dual glass teleprompters used by TV presenters and for U.S. conventions in 1964;<ref name=Getty>{{cite web|url=https://www.gettyimages.co.uk/album/kiss-and-teleprompter-a-look-back-at--ZSKiLqlWBUaxLQhi1gvBTg#attorney-general-robert-kennedy-smiling-but-with-tears-in-his-eyes-picture-id515489640|title=Kiss and Teleprompter|work=Getty Images|accessdate=3 June 2018}}</ref> to the computer-based rolls of 1982 and the four-prompter system for U.S. conventions which added a large off-stage confidence monitor and inset lectern monitor in 1996;<ref name=DFP>{{cite web|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/99340726/|title=Speakers send a strong message|work=Detroit Free Press (Detroit, Michigan)|date=August 27, 1996|accessdate=3 June 2018}}</ref> to the replacement of glass teleprompters at U.K. political conferences by several large off-stage confidence monitors in 2006;.<ref name=Guardian>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2008/sep/18/liberaldemocrats.libdemconference|title=Bog standard search for Elysium|work=[[The Guardian]]|author=Hoggart, Simon|date=18 September 2008|accessdate=3 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe word ''TelePrompTer'', with [[CamelCase|internal capitalization]], originated as a [[trade name]] used by the TelePrompTer Company, which first developed the device in the 1950s; it is now a [[genericized trademark]]. [[Autocue]], a [[United Kingdom]] manufacturer of teleprompters, also finds its trademark used in a generic fashion in [[Commonwealth of Nations|Commonwealth]] countries and some European countries.\n\n==History==\n[[File:LBJ Civil Rights Act crowd.jpg|right|thumb|U.S. President [[Lyndon B. Johnson]] uses a teleprompter while announcing the [[Civil Rights Act of 1964]].]]\nThe [[TelePrompTer Corporation]] was founded in the 1950s by [[Fred Barton, Jr.]], [[Hubert Schlafly]] and [[Irving Berlin Kahn]]. Barton was an [[actor]] who suggested the [[concept]] of the teleprompter as a means of assisting [[television]] performers who had to memorize large amounts of material in a short time.<ref>{{Cite book\n| publisher = The Difference\n| isbn = 0-9767761-0-3\n| last = Brown\n| first = Laurie\n| title = The Teleprompter Manual\n| date = 2005-12-28\n}}</ref>\nSchlafly built the first teleprompter in 1950. It was simply a mechanical device, operated by a hidden technician, located near the camera.<ref>Engineers' Device Eased Speechmakers' Minds, Wall Street Journal, April 26, 2011, p.A6</ref> The script, in inch-high letters, was printed by a special electric typewriter on a paper scroll, which was advanced as the performer read, and the machines rented for the then-considerable sum of $30 per hour.<ref>\"TV's Cost-Cutting Gadets,\" Sponsor, 22 September 1952, 36. [http://americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Sponsor-Magazine/1952/Sponsor-1952-09-2.pdf Green Bay-de Pere Telephone Directory {{!}} Even Our Phone Number Tells Our Story... ADAMS 1 \u2192 TV gadgets that save money for sponsors]</ref> In 1952 former President [[Herbert Hoover]] used a Schlafly-designed speech teleprompter to address the [[1952 Republican National Convention]] in [[Chicago, Illinois|Chicago]]. U.S. Governor [[Paul A. Dever]] spoke at the [[1952 Democratic National Convention]], also held in Chicago, using a mechanical-roll teleprompter on a long pole held by a TV technician in the convention audience, while the [[1952 Republican National Convention]] used a smaller teleprompter placed in front of the speaker's rostrum.<ref name=Smithsonian/> Mechanical prompters were still being used as late as 1992, as was the case with ''[[The Tonight Show Starring Johnny Carson]]''.{{citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\nOn January 4, 1954,<ref>\"Ike Uses Pair of Teleprompters.\" Cleveland Plain Dealer, January 6, 1954, p. 13.</ref> [[Dwight Eisenhower]] was the first President to use a teleprompter for a State of the Union address.<ref>[http://www.smithsonianmag.com/history-archaeology/A-Brief-History-of-the-Teleprompter-175411341.html A Brief History of the Teleprompter]</ref>\n\n[[Jess Oppenheimer]], who created ''[[I Love Lucy]]'' and served for its first five years as its producer and head writer, developed the first \"in-the-lens\" prompter<ref name=\"Oppenheimer\">Laughs, [https://books.google.com/books?id=7fW-rGDmGxIC&pg=PA204 Luck...and Lucy: How I Came to Create the Most Popular Sitcom of All Time, by Jess Oppenheimer with Gregg Oppenheimer], pp. 204-205.</ref> and was awarded U.S. patents<ref>{{cite patent|US|2883902}}</ref><ref>{{cite patent|US|2926559}}</ref> for its creation. This system uses a mirror to reflect a script onto a piece of glass placed in front of the camera lens, thus allowing the reader to look directly into the camera. First used by [[Lucille Ball]] and [[Desi Arnaz]] in 1953<ref name=\"Oppenheimer\"/> to read commercials on-camera, it soon became a staple of [[television news]] and is the primary system used with prompters today.\n\nThe first [[personal computer]]-based teleprompter, Compu=Prompt appeared in 1982. It was invented and marketed by Courtney M. Goodin and Laurence B. Abrams in Los Angeles, California. The custom software and specially-redesigned camera hardware ran on the Atari 800 Personal Computer, which featured smooth hardware-assisted scrolling. Their company later became ProPrompt, Inc., which is still providing teleprompting services over 32 years later. Other paper-based teleprompting companies Electronic Script Prompting, QTV and Telescript followed suit and developed their own software several years later, when computers with enough graphics power to provide the smooth scrolling text became available. In January 2010 Compu=Prompt received a Technology and Engineering Emmy Award for \"Pioneering Development in Electronic Prompting\".\n\n==Etymology==\n[[File:teleprompter.jpg|thumb|A teleprompter displaying text]]{{Unreferenced section|date=June 2017}}\n\nThe word \"TelePrompTer\", with [[CamelCase|internal capitalization]], originated as a [[trade name]] used by the TelePrompTer Company, which first developed the device in the 1950s. The word \"teleprompter\", with no capitalization, has become a [[genericized trademark]], because it is used to refer to similar systems manufactured by many different companies. The [[United States Patent Office]] does not have any live trademarks registered for the word ''teleprompter'', but this does not rule out the possibility of a company enforcing the trademark without registering it. Some other common terms for this type of device are:\n* [[Autocue]] (the trademark of Autocue Group Ltd, most commonly used in [[Commonwealth of Nations|Commonwealth]] countries)\n* electronic speech notes\n* cueing device\n* idiot board (slang)\n\n==Modern design==\n\n===Television===\n[[File:Teleprompter in use.jpg|thumb|right|230px|Teleprompter in use]]\n\nModern teleprompters for [[news program]]s consist of a [[personal computer]], connected to [[video monitor]]s on each [[professional video camera]]. In certain systems, the PC connects to a separate display device to offer greater flexibility in setup, distances and cabling. The monitors are often black-and-white and have the scanning reversed to compensate for the reflection of the [[mirror]]. A [[peripheral device]] attached has a knob that can be turned to speed up, slow down, or even reverse the scrolling of the text. The text is usually displayed in white letters on a black background for the best readability, while cues are in inverse video ([[light-on-dark color scheme|black on white]]). Difficult words (mainly international names) are spelled out [[phonetic]]ally,<ref>[http://uk.reuters.com/article/idUKN2540350420070926 Reuters: When words get in the way, Bush goes phonetic]</ref> as are other particulars like \"Nine-eleven\" (to specify that the event [[September 11 attacks|9/11]] should not be [[pronunciation|pronounced]] \"[[9-1-1|nine-one-one]]\", for example).\n\nWith the development of inexpensive teleprompter [[software application]]s as well as free Web-based teleprompter applets, many different disciplines are now using teleprompters to help them deliver sermons, deliver speeches, and to create quality audio recordings. Unlike their more advanced counterparts, these entry level products work on desktop computers, laptop computers, and even tablet computers to enable the speaker to control the rate and flow of their speech. They are also used by many different organizations and schools to deliver prewritten information by relative novices. They are usually called \"personal teleprompters.\"\n\n===Presidential (or glass) teleprompters===\n[[File:SOU2007.jpg|thumb|right|230px|[[George W. Bush]] next to two glass teleprompters. They can be seen more clearly by clicking on this image and the one below.]]\n[[File:Joe Biden 2008 DNC (1).jpg|thumb|right|230px|[[Joe Biden]] flanked by two glass teleprompters. The two teleprompter monitors are embedded in the floor of the podium.]]\n\nGlass teleprompters were first used at the [[1956 Democratic National Convention]]. The inventor of the teleprompter, Hubert Schlafly, explained that he wanted to create a less obtrusive teleprompting system than the ones used at the time. He said, \"We developed a 'one way mirror' device we called the ''Speech View'' system... The prompter, hidden in the base, reflected the text on the glass to the speaker while the audience looked through the glass without being aware of the text. Two such prompters, one on the right and one on the left of the speaker allowed him to switch from one to the other and appear to address the entire audience\".<ref name=TTM>Laurie Brown, ''The Teleprompter Manual'' (Pleasant Ridge, Michigan: The Difference Press, 2006), pp. 5\u20136. {{ISBN|0-9767761-0-3}}.</ref>\n\nSchlafly's company then created a speaker's lectern that included two synchronized glass teleprompters and a range of technological innovations including air conditioning and an adjustable-height speaker's platform. The success of the system led the company to develop a new model for use on TV cameras, with the glass placed directly in front of the lens. The camera \"looked through the glass; the performer looked directly at the TV audience and was able to read the text word for word. This device now has worldwide use\".<ref name=TTM/>\n\nTypically, a screen on either side of the speaker shows mirrored text from upward-facing floor monitors at the base of a stand supporting a [[one-way mirror]] at the top, angled down towards the screen. The speaker sees the text on the screen reflected in the mirror, while the audience sees what looks like a sheet of tinted glass on each side of the speaker.\n\nSchlafly's glass teleprompters were also used for the [[1956 Republican National Convention]], and at both parties' conventions from then on. In 1964, glass teleprompters were used by [[Robert F. Kennedy]], at the time the [[United States Attorney General|U.S. Attorney General]], who served in both the [[Presidency of John F. Kennedy|Kennedy]] and early [[Presidency of Lyndon B. Johnson|Johnson]] Administrations (1961-1964), to deliver his convention speech.<ref name=Getty/>\n\n===Confidence monitors===\n[[File:2012 DNC day 2 (7958010012).jpg|thumb|right|230px|(A) The first three teleprompters: A monitor screen partly-embedded in the lectern's desk top displays the scrolling text of the speech in synchrony with two screens embedded in the podium floor. They are on either side of the speaker, reflected by the angled glass teleprompters above them. Click this image and the ones below to see the four-teleprompter system more clearly.]]\n[[File:2012 DNC day 3 Brian Schweitzer (7959825568).jpg|thumb|right|230px|(B) The fourth teleprompter: A large confidence monitor displays the scrolling text of the speech immediately below the lenses of the broadcast TV cameras, several metres/feet away from the speaker.]]\n[[File:Barack_Obama_Denver_Speech_2008.jpg|thumb|right|230px|(C) The above-described four-teleprompter set-up in use at the [[2008 Democratic National Convention]] in [[Denver]], [[Colorado]], USA (the large confidence monitor under the TV cameras is near the bottom far right of this frame).]]\n\nIn 1996, for the first time, speakers at the ''[[1996 Democratic National Convention|Democratic National Convention]]'', held at the [[United Center]] in [[Chicago]], Illinois, used a four-teleprompter system: as can be seen at another convention in image (A) on the right, the first three prompters are placed to the left, right and in front of the speaker, the latter embedded within the speaker's [[lectern]], enabling the speaker to look down at the lectern without losing his/her place in the text of the speech; while in image (B) below it, the fourth prompter is a large confidence monitor located immediately below the lenses of the TV broadcast cameras, at a distance of several metres/yards from the speaker.\n\nThis modification to the traditional two-teleprompter set-up continues to be in use at both the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] and [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] parties' national conventions: the two glass teleprompters on either side of the speaker's lectern create the illusion that the speaker is looking directly at the audience in the hall, the monitor embedded in the lectern, together with the fourth, much larger teleprompter screen, known as a 'confidence monitor', placed immediately below the broadcast TV cameras which are located some distance away from the convention stage on a specially-constructed broadcasting gantry. This placement of the center prompter creates the illusion that the speaker is periodically looking straight into the camera lens, and thereby appears to directly address the TV audience watching the televised Convention coverage.<ref name=DFP/>\n\nIn 2006, speakers at the ''[[Liberal Democrat Federal Conference]]'', held at the [[Brighton Centre]] in [[Brighton]], UK, also used a three-screen system (but this time consisting entirely of large off-stage confidence monitors mounted on poles \u2014 which are often described outside [[North America]], together with glass teleprompters, as \"[[autocue]]s\"), where the skill required for those using it, according to the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]]' former leader, [[Menzies Campbell]] (2006\u20142008), is to move their gaze seamlessly from one screen to the other: left, centre (near the broadcast TV cameras), right and then back again.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=W38dAwAAQBAJ&pg=PT248&lpg=PT248&dq=%22menzies+campbell+my+autobiography%22+autocues&source=bl&ots=tChf4KOF4O&sig=MeKqS7d9_OS3htvVbfUATPI5zG0&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiSksjY8aTbAhXlCMAKHRMaBR8Q6AEIJzAA#v=onepage&q=%22menzies%20campbell%20my%20autobiography%22%20autocues&f=false|title=Menzies Campbell: My Autobiography|author=Campbell, Menzies|work=Hachette Books, London|date=2014|accessdate=27 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nAs well as helping the speaker to appear to sometimes directly address the TV audience during his/her speech, this system also allows the speaker \u2014 in another case cited, the party's then-new leader, [[Nick Clegg]] (2008\u20142015) \u2014 to abandon the podium lectern and roam the stage, speaking with apparent spontaneity but in fact constantly assisted by three large autocue screens placed throughout the conference hall.<ref name=Guardian/> Ironically, this use of the system was adopted by Clegg to counter the oratorical success of another party leader, [[David Cameron]] (later to become British Prime Minister), who bestrode stages while speaking seemingly off-the-cuff, having memorized key parts of his speech.<ref name=Atkinson>{{cite web|url=http://maxatkinson.blogspot.co.uk/2009/09/cleggs-conference-speech-definitely-ok.html|title=Clegg\u2019s conference speech: 'definitely OK, absolutely fine, without any doubt not bad'|author=Atkinson, Max|date=24 September 2009|accessdate=27 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nThis multiple use of off-stage confidence monitors also dispenses with the need for glass teleprompters to be present on the conference stage, thereby reducing \"stage clutter\", and removes the inevitable restrictions on the speaker's movement and field of vision imposed by on-stage glass prompters. The disadvantage of such a system is that the provision of \"giant teleprompters\" becomes essential to maintaining the illusion of speaking with apparent spontaneity.<ref name=Atkinson/>\n\n'''<big>Teleprompters in India</big>'''\n[[Harish Bhimani]], a National Awardee in Voiceovers pioneered the age of teleprompters in India, was quoted as saying:\n\n<blockquote>\nThe Teleprompter has been on my wish list since way back in 1978 when I went to the US on a holiday. During this visit, a trip to the news-room of a TV channel was my top priority \u2013 certainly more than a visit to the Statue of Liberty! Being an established newscaster on TV back in India, I was very keen to see how the broadcasting fraternity functioned in the most advanced country in the world.\n\nThe first thing that struck him was the level of professionalism in their approach.\n\nIn a nut-shell, if you are expected to give a top-notch performance, you also received the best facilities to make such a performance possible. That is when I first saw a TELEPROMPTER!\n\nIt was a dream! No shuffling of haphazardly scribbled news items on sheets of paper! A visibly relaxed expression, with an added ease in impromptu asides! I came back to Mumbai and the daily grind, resigned to the fact that our TV was not yet ready to pamper us 'over-paid' newscasters with a teleprompter.\n</blockquote>\n\nBut the teleprompter stayed with him and he managed to get the first privately owned teleprompter to India in 1992. He then assembled the most suitable model for the then prevailing Indian conditions \u2013 including the [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=n0lzuqlTXa8 multi-lingual milieu], thus pioneering tele prompting in India.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Cue card]]\n* A similar device called an interrotron is often used by filmmaker [[Errol Morris]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Nobile, Jr |first1=Phil |title=The Interrotron: How Errol Morris Changed The Way Documentaries Watch Us |url=https://birthmoviesdeath.com/2017/07/07/the-interrotron-how-errol-morris-changed-the-way-documentaries-watch-us |website=Birth.Movies.Death. |language=en |date=7 July 2017}}</ref> Instead of text, a live image of the interviewer (or the interviewee) is displayed, allowing both conversation partners to look straight at the camera.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Pavlus |first1=John |title=Errol Morris\u2019s Secret Weapon for Unsettling Interviews: The Interrotron |url=https://www.fastcompany.com/1663105/errol-morriss-secret-weapon-for-unsettling-interviews-the-interrotron |website=Fast Company |date=30 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Teleprompters}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120107211123/http://www.emmyonline.tv/mediacenter/tech_2k9_winners.html 2010 Engineering & Technology Emmy Awards for Prompting]\n\n[[Category:American inventions]]\n[[Category:Film and video technology]]\n[[Category:Television technology]]\n[[Category:Television terminology]]\n", "name_user": "Mrschimpf", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEtymology", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Teleprompter"}
{"title_page": "Star Twinkle PreCure", "text_new": "{{Infobox animanga/Header\n| name            = Star Twinkle PreCure\n| image           = Twinkleprecure.jpg\n| image_size      = 250px\n| landscape       = yes\n| caption         = Key visual of the series featuring the five main Cures. From left to right: Cure Cosmo, Cure Milky, Cure Star, Cure Selene and Cure Soleil. Mascots Fuwa and Prunce are visible near the bottom-right and top-left corners respectively. \n| ja_kanji        = \u30b9\u30bf\u30fc\u2606\u30c8\u30a5\u30a4\u30f3\u30af\u30eb\u30d7\u30ea\u30ad\u30e5\u30a2\n| ja_romaji       = Sut\u0101 Touinkuru Purikyua\n| genre           = [[Magical girl]]<!-- Note: Use and cite reliable sources to identify genre/s, not personal interpretation. Please don't include more than three genres (per [[MOS:A&M]]). -->\n}}\n{{Infobox animanga/Video\n| type            = tv series\n| director        = [[jp:\u5bae\u5143\u5b8f\u5f70|Hiroaki Miyamoto]]\n| producer        = Akari Yanagawa\n| writer          = Isao Murayama\n| music           = [[Yuki Hayashi (composer)|Yuki Hayashi]] <br/> Asami Tachibana\n| studio          = [[Toei Animation]]\n| network         = [[All-Nippon News Network|ANN]] ([[Asahi Broadcasting Corporation|ABC]], [[TV Asahi]])\n| first           = February 3, 2019\n| last            = January 26, 2020\n| episodes        = 49\n| episode_list    = List of Star Twinkle PreCure episodes\n}}\n{{Infobox animanga/Print\n| type            = manga\n| author          = [[Izumi Todo]]\n| illustrator     = [[Futago Kamikita]]\n| publisher       = [[Kodansha]]\n| demographic     = ''[[Sh\u014djo manga|Sh\u014djo]]''\n| imprint         = \n| magazine        = [[Nakayoshi]]\n| first           = February 2019\n| last            = December 2019\n| volumes         = 2\n| volume_list     =\n}}\n{{Infobox animanga/Video\n| type            = film\n| title           = Eiga Star\u2606Twinkle PreCure: Hoshi no Uta ni Omoi wo Komete\n| director        = Y\u016bta Tanaka\n| producer        = \n| writer          = Jin Tanaka\n| music           = Yuki Hayashi <br/> Asami Tachibana\n| studio          = Toei Animation\n| licensee        = \n| released        = {{Start date|2019|10|19}}\n| runtime         = \n}}\n{{Infobox animanga/Footer}}\n{{nihongo|'''''Star Twinkle PreCure'''''|\u30b9\u30bf\u30fc\u2606\u30c8\u30a5\u30a4\u30f3\u30af\u30eb\u30d7\u30ea\u30ad\u30e5\u30a2|Sut\u0101 Touinkuru Purikyua|stylized as '''Star\u2606Twinkle PreCure'''}} is a Japanese [[magical girl]] anime series by [[Toei Animation]]. It is the first ''[[Pretty Cure]]'' series released in the [[Reiwa]] period<ref>The series's first 13 episodes were aired during the last days of the [[Heisei]] period, with the [[Reiwa]] Period beginning on May 1, 2019. Despite being aired in the last days in the Heisei period, it was officially recognized as a Reiwa series for consistency.</ref> and the sixteenth installment of the franchise, featuring the fourteenth generation of Cures. It is directed by [[jp:\u5bae\u5143\u5b8f\u5f70|Hiroaki Miyamoto]] (''[[One Piece Film: Gold]]'') and written by Isao Murayama. The series aired on all [[All-Nippon News Network|ANN]] stations in Japan from February 3, 2019 to January 26, 2020, succeeding ''[[Hugtto! PreCure]]'' in its initial time slot.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.toei-anim.co.jp/tv/startwinkle_precure/|title=\u30b9\u30bf\u30fc\u2606\u30c8\u30a5\u30a4\u30f3\u30af\u30eb\u30d7\u30ea\u30ad\u30e5\u30a2 {{!}} \u6771\u6620\u30a2\u30cb\u30e1\u30fc\u30b7\u30e7\u30f3|website=www.toei-anim.co.jp|language=ja|accessdate=2018-12-27}}</ref> It was then succeeded by ''[[Healin' Good PreCure]]'' on February 2, 2020. The series' main topic is [[imagination]], with [[outer space]] and [[constellations]] being the Cures' main motifs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cinematoday.jp/news/N0105869|title=\u53f2\u4e0a\u521d\u30fb\u5b87\u5b99\u4eba\u30d7\u30ea\u30ad\u30e5\u30a2\u767b\u5834\uff01\u3067\u3093\u3071\u7d44.inc\u6210\u702c\u745b\u7f8e\u3089\u300c\u30b9\u30bf\u30fc\u2606\u30c8\u30a5\u30a4\u30f3\u30af\u30eb\u30d7\u30ea\u30ad\u30e5\u30a2\u300d\u58f0\u512a\u767a\u8868|website=\u30b7\u30cd\u30de\u30c8\u30a5\u30c7\u30a4|accessdate=2018-12-27}}</ref>\n\n==Story==\nThe {{nihongo|Starry Sky World|\u661f\u7a7a\u754c|Hoshizora-kai}} is the home to the twelve Star Princesses who are based on the [[Zodiac signs]] and maintain order in the universe. But when the Notraiders attack the Star Palace, the princesses scatter themselves across the universe as the Princess Star Color Pens. Seeking to revive the princesses and avert the universe from being consumed in darkness, the aliens Lala and Prunce travel with the fairy Fuwa to {{nihongo|Mihoshi Town|\u89b3\u661f\u753a|Mihoshi-ch\u014d}} on Earth where they meet the imaginative Hikaru Hoshina. Receiving a Star Color Pendant and one of the Star Color Pens, Hikaru transforms into the legendary PreCure, Cure Star. Joined by Lala and two other girls, Elena and Madoka, as well as the shapeshifting cat-like alien, Yuni, Hikaru leads the Star Twinkle PreCure as they seek to revive the Star Princesses and fight against the Notraiders.<ref name=\"story\"/>\n\n==Characters==\nThe titular characters are a team of magical girls who use the rocket ship that Lala came to Earth in to travel through space. They derive their powers from the Star Color Pendant and {{nihongo|Star Color Pens|\u30b9\u30bf\u30fc\u30ab\u30e9\u30fc\u30da\u30f3|Sut\u0101 Kar\u0101 Pen}}, tasked to collect the twelve {{nihongo|Princess Star Color Pens|\u30d7\u30ea\u30f3\u30bb\u30b9\u30b9\u30bf\u30fc\u30ab\u30e9\u30fc\u30da\u30f3|Purinsesu Sut\u0101 Kar\u0101 Pen}} needed for their mission to revive the Star Princesses.\n<!-- Remember to keep the names in Western order outside the Nihongo romanization -->\n;{{nihongo|Hikaru Hoshina|\u661f\u5948 \u3072\u304b\u308b|Hoshina Hikaru|extra2=/}} {{nihongo|Cure Star|\u30ad\u30e5\u30a2\u30b9\u30bf\u30fc|Kyua Sut\u0101}}<ref name=\":0\"/>\n:{{Voiced by|[[Eimi Naruse]]}}\n:A second year middle school girl who loves [[stars]] and constellations. She is cheerful and full of imagination, but also stubborn and often acts on intuition. She enjoys looking at the stars and writing in her notebook, which has turned into the \"Twinkle Book.\" As the [[pink]]-colored Cure Star, whose motif is stars, her main technique is \"Star Punch\" which can be upgraded into stronger variations by using a Princess Star Color Pen. In the last episode, Hikaru became an astronaut just like she promised Lala.\n;{{nihongo|Lala Hagoromo|\u7fbd\u8863 \u30e9\u30e9|Hagoromo Rara|extra2=/}} {{nihongo|Cure Milky|\u30ad\u30e5\u30a2\u30df\u30eb\u30ad\u30fc|Kyua Miruk\u012b}}<ref name=\":0\"/>\n:{{Voiced by|[[Konomi Kohara]]}}\n:The first alien to become a Pretty Cure,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.oricon.co.jp/news/2129237/full/|title=\u300e\u30d7\u30ea\u30ad\u30e5\u30a2\u300f\u30b7\u30ea\u30fc\u30ba\u521d\u306e\u5b87\u5b99\u4eba\u30d7\u30ea\u30ad\u30e5\u30a2\u8a95\u751f \u5929\u306e\u5ddd\u306e\u30d7\u30ea\u30ad\u30e5\u30a2\u30fb\u30ad\u30e5\u30a2\u30df\u30eb\u30ad\u30fc|website=[[Oricon News]]|language=ja|accessdate=August 23, 2019}}</ref> Lala is from the planet {{nihongo|Samaan|\u30b5\u30de\u30fc\u30f3|Sam\u0101n}} who came with Prunce and Fuwa to find the Precure on Earth and ends up becoming one herself. While her presence on Earth is considered illegal according to space laws, she is allowed to remain on Earth under an alias. While serious and responsible, she sometimes makes mistakes while having trouble getting accustomed to Earth's people and customs. As the [[Teal (color)|teal]]-colored Cure Milky, whose motif is the [[Milky Way]] and hearts, her main technique is \"Milky Shock\" which can be upgraded into stronger variations by using a Princess Star Color Pen. In the last episode, Lala became a doctor of the A.I.\n;{{nihongo|Elena Amamiya|\u5929\u5bae \u3048\u308c\u306a|Amamiya Erena|extra2=/}} {{nihongo|Cure Soleil|\u30ad\u30e5\u30a2\u30bd\u30ec\u30a4\u30e6|Kyua Soreiyu}}<ref name=\":0\"/>\n:{{Voiced by|[[Kiyono Yasuno]]}}\n:A popular third year middle school student with a radiant smile and athletic prowess, referred to as the \"Sun of Mihoshi Town.\" A [[h\u0101fu]] who is [[Mexicans|Mexican]] on her father's side, her family own the Sonrisa Flower shop where she works part time while looking after her younger siblings. As the [[yellow]] and [[Orange (colour)|orange]]-colored Cure Soleil, whose motif is the [[sun]], her main technique is \"Soleil Shoot\" which can be upgraded into stronger variations by using a Princess Star Color Pen. In the last episode, Elena became a tv interpreter for the media coverage.\n;{{nihongo|Madoka Kaguya|\u9999\u4e45\u77e2 \u307e\u3069\u304b|Kaguya Madoka|extra2=/}} {{nihongo|Cure Selene|\u30ad\u30e5\u30a2\u30bb\u30ec\u30fc\u30cd|Kyua Ser\u0113ne}}<ref name=\":0\"/>\n:{{Voiced by|[[Mikako Komatsu]]}}\n:A third year middle school student who is the student council president of Hikaru's school, referred to as the \"Moon of Mihoshi Town\". Her father works for the government, and her mother is a pianist. She often strives to be ladylike and is sweet, but can be blunt at times. She is multi-talented in archery, piano, and flower arrangements. As the [[purple]]-colored Cure Selene, whose motif is the [[moon]], her main technique is \"Selene Arrow\" which can be upgraded into stronger variations by using a Princess Star Color Pen. In the last episode, Madoka took her dad's job as the Space Investigator.\n;{{nihongo|Yuni|\u30e6\u30cb|Yuni|extra2=/}} {{nihongo|Cure Cosmo|\u30ad\u30e5\u30a2\u30b3\u30b9\u30e2|Kyua Kosumo}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.toei-anim.co.jp/tv/startwinkle_precure/news/2019053101.php|title=\u4e0a\u5742\u3046\u3048\u3055\u304b\u3059\u307f\u308c\uff08\u30de\u30aa\uff0f\u30d6\u30eb\u30fc\u30ad\u30e3\u30c3\u30c8\uff0f\u30ad\u30e5\u30a2\u30b3\u30b9\u30e2\u5f79\uff09}}</ref>\n:{{Voiced by|[[Sumire Uesaka]]}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.toei-anim.co.jp/tv/startwinkle_precure/news/2019051101.php|title=\u4e0a\u5742\u3059\u307f\u308c\uff08\u30de\u30aa\u5f79\uff09}}</ref> \n:A shapeshifting [[Catgirl (anime and manga)|catgirl]] from the Planet Rainbow whose people were turned into stone as the result of Aiwarn's experiments. Using a perfume to assist with her shapeshifting, with her ears and tail always remaining, Yuni has searched for a way to restore her people by assuming the identities of phantom thief {{nihongo|Blue Cat|\u30d6\u30eb\u30fc\u30ad\u30e3\u30c3\u30c8|Bur\u016b Kyatto}} to steal stolen treasures, the intergalactic pop idol {{nihongo|Mao|\u30de\u30aa|Mao}} to gather information, and Aiwarn's butler assistant {{nihongo|Bakenyan|\u30d0\u30b1\u30cb\u30e3\u30fc\u30f3|Bakeny\u0101n}} ({{Voiced by|[[Y\u014dji Ueda]]}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.toei-anim.co.jp/tv/startwinkle_precure/news/2019030901.php|title=\u4e0a\u7530 \u71ff\u53f8\uff08\u30d0\u30b1\u30cb\u30e3\u30fc\u30f3 \u5f79\uff09}}</ref>) to infiltrate the Notraiders. After becoming a Precure, Yuni joins Hikaru and the others to search for the pens with them. As the [[blue]] and [[rainbow]]-colored Cure Cosmo, whose motif is the [[rainbow]], she is armed with the Rainbow Perfume which she uses in her \"Cosmo Shining\" technique with its \"Rainbow Splash\" variation using a Princess Star Color Pen. In the last episode, Yuni is seen with Olyfio as they watch Hikaru being launched into space.\n\n===Starry Sky World===\n;{{nihongo|Fuwa|\u30d5\u30ef}}<ref name=\":0\"/>\n:{{Voiced by|[[Hina Kino]]}}\n: A baby fairy with the power to create portals through space who was created by the Star Princesses as both a means of reviving them and stopping Ophiuchus, normally residing in the Twinkle Book. After the Star Princess Pens have been gathered, Fuwa is transformed into a unicorn-like fairy with the PreCure told to help her reach her full potential by acquiring their Twinkle Imagination as part of the Star Princesses' plan to destroy Ophiuchus. Despite learning that absorbing the Cures' Twinkle Imagination would ultimately destroy her as well in the process, Fuwa proceeds in the attempt to eliminate Ophiuchus and fails. Fuwa is later revived after the Cures defeated Ophiuchus, but lost her memories and powers.\n;{{nihongo|Prunce|\u30d7\u30eb\u30f3\u30b9|Purunsu}}<ref name=\":0\"/>\n:{{voiced by|[[Hiroyuki Yoshino]]}}\n: An UFO-like alien who serves the Star Princesses and came to Earth with Lala to seek the PreCure.\n;{{nihongo|AI|\u3048\u30fc\u3042\u3044}}\n:{{Voiced by|[[Miki It\u014d]]}}\n: The [[artificial intelligence]] system of the rocket.\n;{{nihongo|Abraham|\u30a2\u30d6\u30e9\u30cf\u30e0|Aburahamu}}\n:{{Voiced by|[[Yutaka Aoyama]]}}\n:An alien from Planet Minitur who assumed a form of a film director so he can test the Precure's determination to have Lala stay on Earth.\n\n====Star Princesses====\nThe {{nihongo|'''Star Princesses'''|\u30b9\u30bf\u30fc\u30d7\u30ea\u30f3\u30bb\u30b9|Sut\u0101 Purinsesu}} are thirteen princesses who protect the balance of the universe, with Ophiuchus originally a member before she turned her back on them when they decided to transfer half of their power to bestow all life in the universe with imagination. The Star Princesses used the rest of their power to create Fuwa and used their remaining strength to drive the Notraiders away, which scatter across the universe as the Princess Star Color Pens sought by the Precure and the Notraiders. Each princess represents one of the 12 Zodiac signs.\n\n;{{nihongo|Taurus|\u304a\u3046\u3057\u5ea7|Oushi-za}}\n:{{Voiced by|[[Ayako Kawasumi]]}}\n:The Star Princess based on [[Taurus (constellation)|Taurus]], whose pink Princess Star Color Pen was found on Earth.\n;{{nihongo|Leo|\u3057\u3057\u5ea7|Shishi-za}}\n:{{Voiced by|[[Madoka Yonezawa]]}}\n:The Star Princess based on [[Leo (constellation)|Leo]], whose cyan Princess Star Color Pen was found on Earth.\n;{{nihongo|Libra|\u3066\u3093\u3073\u3093\u5ea7|Tenbin-za}}\n:{{Voiced by|[[Mako (voice actress)|Mako]]}}\n:The Star Princess based on [[Libra (constellation)|Libra]], whose yellow Princess Star Color Pen with found on Planet Kennel.\n;{{nihongo|Capricorn|\u3084\u304e\u5ea7|Yagi-za}}\n:{{Voiced by|[[Marika Hayashi]]}}\n:The Star Princess based on [[Capricornus (constellation)|Capricornus]], whose magenta Princess Star Color Pen was in the Notraiders' possession before the Precure took it.\n;{{nihongo|Scorpio|\u3055\u305d\u308a\u5ea7|Sasori-za}}\n:{{Voiced by|Unknown}}\n:The Star Princess based on [[Scorpius (constellation)|Scorpius]], whose orange Princess Star Color Pen was in the Notraiders' possession before the Precure took it.\n;{{nihongo|Sagittarius|\u3044\u3066\u5ea7|Ite-za}}\n:{{Voiced by|Unknown}}\n:The Star Princess based on [[Sagittarius (constellation)|Sagittarius]], whose lilac Princess Star Color Pen was found on planet Zeni.\n;{{nihongo|Virgo|\u304a\u3068\u3081\u5ea7|Otome-za}}\n:{{Voiced by|Unknown}}\n:The Star Princess based on [[Virgo (constellation)|Virgo]], whose white Princess Star Color Pen was found on planet Zeni.\n;{{nihongo|Gemini|\u3075\u305f\u3054\u5ea7|Futago-za}}\n:{{Voiced by|Unknown}}\n:Star Princess twin sisters based on [[Gemini (constellation)|Gemini]], whose teal Princess Star Color Pen was found on planet Rainbow.\n;{{nihongo|Aries|\u304a\u3072\u3064\u3058\u5ea7|Ohitsuji-za}}\n:{{Voiced by|Unknown}}\n:The Star Princess based on [[Aries (constellation)|Aries]], whose red Princess Star Color Pen was found on planet Kumarin.\n;{{nihongo|Aquarius|\u307f\u305a\u304c\u3081\u5ea7|Mizugame-za}}\n:{{Voiced by|Unknown}}\n:The Star Princess based on [[Aquarius (constellation)|Aquarius]], whose blue Princess Star Color Pen was found on planet Icesnow.\n;{{nihongo|Cancer|\u304b\u306b\u5ea7|Kani-za}}\n:{{Voiced by|Unknown}}\n:The Star Princess based on [[Cancer (constellation)|Cancer]], whose green Princess Star Color Pen was found on planet Saman.\n;{{nihongo|Pisces|\u3046\u304a\u5ea7|Uo-za}}\n:{{Voiced by|Unknown}}\n:The Star Princess based on [[Pisces (constellation)|Pisces]], whose light pink Princess Star Color Pen was found somewhere floating in space.\n\n===Notraiders===\nThe {{nihongo|'''Notraiders'''|\u30ce\u30c3\u30c8\u30ec\u30a4\u30c0\u30fc|Nottoreid\u0101}}, the main antagonists of the series, who originate from the darkest and forgotten parts of the universe, are an intergalactic army of space raiders seeking universal dominion by obtaining all the Princess Star Color Pens to purge the universe of all light and give its power to their leader. Later, they seek to capture Fuwa as a vessel. Their leading members are based on the [[Y\u014dkai|yokai]] from [[Japanese mythology]]. The name \"Notto\" means take over (\u4e57\u3063\u53d6\u308b).\n\n====Leaders====\n;{{nihongo|Darknest / Ophiuchus|\u30c0\u30fc\u30af\u30cd\u30b9\u30c8 / \u3078\u3073\u3064\u304b\u3044\u5ea7|D\u0101kunesuto / Hebitsukai-Za}}\n:{{Voiced by|[[Mie Sonozaki]]}}<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.animatetimes.com/news/details.php?id=1578131411|title=\u300e\u30b9\u30bf\u30fc\u2606\u30c8\u30a5\u30a4\u30f3\u30af\u30eb\u30d7\u30ea\u30ad\u30e5\u30a2\u300f\u30c0\u30fc\u30af\u30cd\u30b9\u30c8\u306e\u6b63\u4f53\u304c\u5224\u660e\uff01\u3000\u6f14\u3058\u308b\u306e\u306f\u58f0\u512a\u30fb\u5712\u5d0e\u672a\u6075\u3055\u3093\u3001\u71b1\u3044\u60f3\u3044\u306e\u30b3\u30e1\u30f3\u30c8\u3082\u5927\u516c\u958b}}</ref>\n:Leader of the Notraiders and the primary antagonist of the series, [[Ophiuchus]] is actually a former member of the Star Princesses who became disillusioned with the universe they created when her fellow princesses voted against her to bestow half of their collective power to all life in the form of imagination. This influenced her to turn on her fellow princesses before they exiled her, eventually regaining her strength and assuming the identity of Darknest, a snake-armored figure with an Uwabami-like serpent wrapped around her body, to consume all light in the universe. But Ophiuchus eventually discards her disguise and minions, capturing Fuwa and the Star Princesses to conduct a ritual to unmake the universe. After surviving the Star Princesses's gambit to destroy her through Fuwa, Ophiuchus is ultimately defeated by the Precures and accepts her loss while vowing to return if things become twisted again.\n\n;{{nihongo|Garuouga|\u30ac\u30eb\u30aa\u30a6\u30ac|Garuouga}}\n:{{Voiced by|Satoshi Tsuruoka}}<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.toei-anim.co.jp/tv/startwinkle_precure/news/2019022301.php|title=\u9db4\u5ca1 \u8061\uff08\u30ac\u30eb\u30aa\u30a6\u30ac \u5f79\uff09}}</ref>\n:Second-in command of the Notraiders, he is an [[oni]]-like alien who became Darknest's follower after his planet was destroyed with the promise of power. His bracelet can also increase the commanders' powers and has a powerful physical strength to inflict damage on his opponents. During his final battle, he battles the Cures until learning of Darknest's identity as Ophiuchus and she destroyed the world. Garouoga attempts to kill Ophiuchus before she places him and the commanders under her control by twisting their imagination, the Cures purify them before Aiwarn takes them to safety.\n\n====Commanders====\nGaruouga's subordinates who aid in reviving Darknest, each using different method to battle the Pretty Cures to hinder their mission. Garuouga later increase their powers, with Darknest upgrading their abilities further.\n;{{nihongo|Kappard|\u30ab\u30c3\u30d1\u30fc\u30c9|Kapp\u0101do}}\n:{{Voiced by|[[Yoshimasa Hosoya]]}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.toei-anim.co.jp/tv/startwinkle_precure/news/2019020201.php|title=\u7d30\u8c37\u4f73\u6b63\uff08\u30ab\u30c3\u30d1\u30fc\u30c9 \u5f79\uff09}}</ref>\n: A [[Kappa (folklore)|kappa]]-like Commander armed with a [[lightsaber]]-like dual blade he uses in his \"Kappard Strike\" attack, originating from a planet that was destroyed as the result of its na\u00efve people being exploited by other races. This motivated Kappard to believe that peoples from other worlds are incapable of coexisting with each other. While initially seeking to capture Fuwa by any means, he is also a warrior who considers the Pretty Cures as worthy opponents. When empowered by Darknest, his blade can now take peoples' imagination and take the form of other weapons. Given a final chance, he confront Hikaru by using his own imagination to further power up his weapon and overpower her first, the Cures manage to defeat him but Darknest teleport him back and absorb him, empower him. During his final battle, he clash with the Cures until he discover Darknest's identity as Ophiuchus, the enraged Kappard attempt to kill her with his allies but she put them under her control by twisting their imagination, the Cures purify them before Aiwarn take them safety.\n;{{nihongo|Tenjou|\u30c6\u30f3\u30b8\u30e7\u30a6|Tenj\u014d}}\n:{{Voiced by|[[Aya End\u014d]]}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.toei-anim.co.jp/tv/startwinkle_precure/news/2019020901.php|title=\u9060\u85e4\u7dbe\uff08\u30c6\u30f3\u30b8\u30e7\u30a6 \u5f79\uff09}}</ref>\n: A playful [[tengu]]-like Commander armed with a fan who originated from Planet Guten, joining the Notraiders over her feelings of being an outcast due to her small nose. Tenjou strategizes her attacks on the Pretty Cures, though she is more interested in the Star Princesses' power than capturing Fuwa. She often use Notrei as [[Human chess]] pieces to fight the Cures, her upgrade by Darknest allowing her to seal a person inside a Nottorei to enhance grunt via their imagination in size and power. In episode 39, 42 and 43, she has rivalry with Elena because they have the same past. When she attack her homeland, Elena understand her feelings and attempt to reconcile with her but she refused. During her final battle, she clash with the Cures until she discover Darknest's identity as Ophiuchus, the enraged Tenjou attempt to kill her with his allies but she put them under her control by twisting their imagination, the Cures purify them before Aiwarn take them safety.\n;{{nihongo|Aiwarn|\u30a2\u30a4\u30ef\u30fc\u30f3|Aiw\u0101n}}\n:{{Voiced by|[[Rie Murakawa]]}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.toei-anim.co.jp/tv/startwinkle_precure/news/2019022301.php|title=\u6751\u5ddd \u68a8\u8863\uff08\u30a2\u30a4\u30ef\u30fc\u30f3 \u5f79\uff09}}</ref>\n: A bratty [[Hitotsume-koz\u014d]]-like Commander armed with a laser pistol who sees others as subjects in her experiments, having petrified the denizens of planet Rainbow to develop the means of corrupting the Princess Star Color Pens into {{nihongo|Dark Pens|\u30c0\u30fc\u30af\u30da\u30f3|D\u0101ku Pen}}. Aiwarn uses the Dark Pens to create Notriggers from her targets' imaginations, the monsters' strength boosted whenever Aiwarn is enhanced by Darknest. Following the revelation that Bakenyan is one of Yuni's disguises, Aiwarn sought revenge on her for being kicked out of the Notraiders while modifying Yuni's spaceship into her personal transforming robot Aiwarn Robo Unit 16. She makes numerous attempts on Yuni's life until she was stopped from petrifying Planet Uranei's residents, with Yuni apologizing to Aiwarn once realizing she had no home other than with the Notraiders. Aiwarn takes her leave after declining Yuni's offer to live on Earth with her and the other Cures. During the final battle, she aids the Cures against her former allies while returning the favor to Yuni by apologizing back to her about how she reacted to Yuni.\n\n====Grunts====\n;{{nihongo|Notrei|\u30ce\u30c3\u30c8\u30ec\u30a4|Nottorei}}\n:{{Voiced by|[[Yoshimitsu Shimoyama]], Kenta Tanaka, Kosuke Echigoya, Yu Miyazaki, Yui Kondo, Sachiko Kojima and Kim Hyang-ri}}\n: The foot-soldiers of the Notraiders who are armed with laser blasters. They later become Tenjou's personal monster after receiving powers from Darknest, which she use peoples' imagination to turn them into giant version of Notrei.\n;{{nihongo|Notrigger|\u30ce\u30c3\u30c8\u30ea\u30ac\u30fc|Nottorig\u0101}}\n:{{Voiced by|Yoshimitsu Shimoyama}}\n: Aiwarn's personal monsters that she creates using a Dark Pen, each Notrigger's form being based on a random object or strong desire from a targeted person's imagination which Aiwarn uses the pen on.\n\n===Hoshina family===\n;{{nihongo|Harukichi Hoshina|\u661f\u5948 \u6625\u5409|Hoshina Harukichi}}\n:{{Voiced by|[[Mitsuru Ogata]]}}\n:Hikaru's grandfather, who has strict rules around the house.\n;{{nihongo|Terumi Hoshina|\u661f\u5948 \u8f1d\u7f8e|Hoshina Terumi}}\n:{{Voiced by|[[Sachiko Kojima]]}}\n:Hikaru's mother, who is a ''[[mangaka]]''.\n;{{nihongo|Yoko Hoshina|\u661f\u5948 \u967d\u5b50|Hoshina Y\u014dko}}\n:{{Voiced by|[[Y\u014dko Asagami]]}}\n:Hikaru's grandmother.\n;{{nihongo|Yoichi Hoshina|\u661f\u5948 \u967d\u4e00|Hoshina Y\u014dichi}}\n:{{Voiced by|[[Akio \u014ctsuka]]}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.toei-anim.co.jp/tv/startwinkle_precure/news/2019070601.php|title=\u5927\u585a \u660e\u592b \uff08\u661f\u5948 \u967d\u4e00\u5f79\uff09}}</ref> \n:Hikaru's father, who works overseas [[Ufology|studying aliens]] and other [[Cryptozoology|cryptids]].\n;{{nihongo|Yeti|\u30a4\u30a8\u30c6\u30a3|Ieti}}\n:{{Voiced by|[[Y\u014dhei Tadano]]}}\n:Hikaru's pet dog.\n\n===Lala's family===\n;{{nihongo|Toto|\u30c8\u30c8|Toto}}\n:{{Voiced by|[[Toshihiko Seki]]}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.toei-anim.co.jp/tv/startwinkle_precure/news/2019082401.php|title=\u95a2 \u4fca\u5f66\uff08\u30c8\u30c8\u5f79\uff09}}</ref>\n:Lala's father, who is an AI Researcher.\n;{{nihongo|Kaka|\u30ab\u30ab|Kaka}}\n:{{Voiced by|[[Fumi Hirano]]}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.toei-anim.co.jp/tv/startwinkle_precure/news/2019082401.php|title=\u5e73\u91ce \u6587\uff08\u30ab\u30ab\u5f79\uff09}}</ref>\n:Lala's mother, who is a Doctor of Rocket Engineering.\n;{{nihongo|Lolo|\u30ed\u30ed|Roro}}\n:{{Voiced by|[[S\u014dma Sait\u014d]]}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.crunchyroll.com/en-gb/anime-news/2019/08/04/danmachi-star-soma-saito-joins-cast-of-star-twinkle-precure|title=DanMachi Star Soma Saito Joins Cast of Star Twinkle PreCure}}</ref>\n:Lala's older twin brother.\n\n=== Amamiya family ===\n;{{nihongo|Carlos|\u30ab\u30eb\u30ed\u30b9|Karurosu}}\n:{{Voiced by|Kentaro Tone}}\n:Elena's father, who is Mexican and the owner of Sonrisa.\n;{{nihongo|Kaede Amamiya|\u5929\u5bae \u304b\u3048\u3067|Amamiya Kaede}}\n:{{Voiced by|[[Ayahi Takagaki]]}}\n:Elena's mother, who is Japanese and an interpreter.\n;{{nihongo|Toma Amamiya|\u5929\u5bae \u3068\u3046\u307e|Amamiya T\u014dma}}, {{nihongo|Reina Amamiya|\u5929\u5bae \u308c\u3044\u306a|Amamiya Reina}}, {{nihongo|Takuto Amamiya|\u5929\u5bae \u305f\u304f\u3068|Amamiya Takuto}}, {{nihongo|Ikuto Amamiya|\u5929\u5bae \u3044\u304f\u3068|Amamiya Ikuto}}, {{nihongo|Anna Amamiya|\u5929\u5bae \u3042\u3093\u306a|Amamiya Anna}}\n:{{Voiced by|Yui Kondo, Mai Nishikawa, [[Healin%27_Good_PreCure#Pretty_Cures|Natsu Yorita]], [[Anzu Haruno]]}}\n:Elena's siblings.\n\n===Kaguya family===\n;{{nihongo|Fuyuki Kaguya|\u9999\u4e45\u77e2 \u51ac\u8cb4|Kaguya Fuyuki}}\n:{{Voiced by|[[Ken Narita]]}}\n:Madoka's stern father who works at the government, perceiving aliens as threat while forbidding his family from keeping secrets.\n;{{nihongo|Mitsuka Kaguya|\u9999\u4e45\u77e2 \u6e80\u4f73|Kaguya Mitsuka}}\n:{{Voiced by|[[Hekiru Shiina]]}}\n:Madoka's mother, who was a famous pianist.\n\n===Yuni's family===\n;{{nihongo|Olyfio|\u30aa\u30ea\u30fc\u30d5\u30a3\u30aa|Or\u012bfio}}\n:{{Voiced by|[[K\u014dki Miyata]]}}\n:The queen of Planet Rainbow.\n\n===Others===\n;{{nihongo|Drams|\u30c9\u30e9\u30e0\u30b9|Doramusu}}\n:{{Voiced by|[[Subaru Kimura]]}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.toei-anim.co.jp/tv/startwinkle_precure/news/2019051101.php|title=\u6728\u6751 \u6634\uff08\u30c9\u30e9\u30e0\u30b9\u5f79\uff09}}</ref>\n:A dragon-like alien from the planet Zeni.\n\n;{{nihongo|Yanyan|\u30e4\u30f3\u30e4\u30f3|Yanyan}}\n:{{Voiced by|[[Asuka Nishi]]}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.toei-anim.co.jp/tv/startwinkle_precure/character/chara9.php|title=\u3068\u308a\u307e\u304f\u4eba\u3005 \u7570\u661f\u4eba {{!}} \u30b9\u30bf\u30fc\u2606\u30c8\u30a5\u30a4\u30f3\u30af\u30eb\u30d7\u30ea\u30ad\u30e5\u30a2 {{!}} \u6771\u6620\u30a2\u30cb\u30e1\u30fc\u30b7\u30e7\u30f3|website=www.toei-anim.co.jp|language=ja|access-date=2019-08-05}}</ref>\n:A hitchhiking [[hermit crab]] alien with a yellow bucket on her back from the planet Pururun.\n\n;{{nihongo|Tatsunori Karube|\u30ab\u30eb\u30d9\u30bf\u30c4\u30ce\u30ea|Karube Tatsunori}}\n:{{Voiced by|[[Junya Enoki]]}}\n:Tatsunori is a classmate.\n\n;{{nihongo|Sakurako Himenojo|\u30d2\u30e1\u30ce\u30b8\u30e7\u3055\u304f\u3089\u3053|Himenoj\u014d Sakurako}}\n:{{Voiced by|[[Y\u014d Taichi]]}}\n:Madoka's classmate.\n\n;{{nihongo|Yumika Nasu|\u30ca\u30b9\u30e6\u30df\u30ab|Nasu Yumika}}\n:{{Voiced by|Makoto Koichi}}\n:Madoka's good friend.\n\n;{{nihongo|Nodoka Hanadera|\u82b1\u5bfa\u306e\u3069\u304b|Hanadera Nodoka}} / {{nihongo|Cure Grace|\u30ad\u30e5\u30a2\u30b0\u30ec\u30fc\u30b9|Kyua Gur\u0113su}}\n:{{anime voice|[[Aoi Y\u016bki]]}}\n:A girl who is the pink-colored Pretty Cure of Flowers from ''[[Healin' Good PreCure]]''.\n\n;{{nihongo|Latte|\u30e9\u30c6|Rate}}\n:{{anime voice|[[Haruka Shiraishi]]}}\n:A brown dog-like fairy from ''Healin' Good PreCure'' who is the {{nihongo|Young Princess of the Healing Garden|\u30d2\u30fc\u30ea\u30f3\u30b0\u30ac\u30fc\u30c7\u30f3\u306e\u5e7c\u3044\u738b\u5973\u3055\u307e}}\n\n===Film only characters===\n;{{nihongo|Piton|\u30d4\u30c8\u30f3|Piton}}\n:{{Voiced by|[[Etsuko Kozakura]]}}\n:A chick-like alien from Planet Miracle. He was good at developing Miracle Lights. He was framed by Yango that caused the malfunction of the factory and seek the Cures to help him clear his name. After Yango's defeat he was appointed as a maker of Miracle Lights.\n;{{nihongo|Yango|\u30e4\u30f3\u30b4|Yango}}\n:{{Voiced by|[[Y\u016bki Kaji]]}}\n:A manipulative and deceptive crow-like alien from Planet Miracle who serves as the main antagonist in ''Precure Miracle Universe''. Working for the president to end the threat around the universe. He was sent to bring Piton and the Cures in because he believe they are responsible for the disappearance of the Miracle light. It was revealed that he caused the malfunction of the factory to frame Piton. The Cures then help Piton expose his corruption and they gather their feelings to purify him, expelling the darkness inside him. \n;{{nihongo|President|\u5927\u7d71\u9818|Dait\u014dry\u014d}}\n:{{Voiced by|[[Yuji Tanaka]]}}\n:An owl-like alien and head of the Planet Miracle.\n;{{nihongo|UMA|\u30e6\u30fc\u30de|Y\u016bma}}\n:A star-like alien that sing, but do not speak and labelled as \"Star Drop\". She befriend the Cures before the alien hunters targets her for bounty. When Burn attempt to capture her, she goes berserk and consumes the planet. Hikaru and Lala's song were able to reach her and she disappeared.\n;{{nihongo|Mary Anne|\u30e1\u30ea\u30fc\u30fb\u30a2\u30f3|Mer\u012b An}}\n:{{Voiced by|[[Rina Chinen]]}}\n:A dog-like alien who is a Starry Sky police detective, instructed to arrest Yuni. She can be a little over the top at times.\n;{{nihongo|Gyro III, Hydro, Burn, Dive, Chop|\u30b8\u30e3\u30a4\u30edIII, \u30cf\u30a4\u30c9\u30ed, \u30d0\u30fc\u30f3, \u30c0\u30a4\u30d6, \u30c1\u30e7\u30c3\u30d7|Jairo III, Haidoro, B\u0101n, Daibu, Choppu}}\n:{{Voiced by|Takayuki Hamatsu, [[Yui Ishikawa]], [[Shunsuke Sakuya]], [[Jin Katagiri]], and Ry\u016bsuke Komakine<ref>https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2019-09-04/star-twinkle-precure-anime-film-reveals-guest-cast-for-5-alien-hunters/.150706</ref>}}\n:A gang of five alien hunters targeting the UMA. They are the main antagonists of the movie. They invade Earth to capture UMA to collect a bounty but were confronted by the Cures, the girls were able to defeat them but Burn attemp to capture UMA which caused her to go berserk. After UMA's departure, the hunters are all incarcerated.\n\n==Media==\n\n===Anime===\n{{see also|List of Star Twinkle PreCure episodes}}\n'' Star Twinkle PreCure'' was announced on November 28, 2018,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2018-11-28/toei-confirms-star-twinkle-precure-tv-anime-for-2019/.140086|title=Toei Confirms Star Twinkle Precure TV Anime for 2019|website=Anime News Network|language=en|accessdate=2018-12-27}}</ref> following a trademark filing reported on October 5, 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/daily-briefs/2018-10-23/star-twinkle-precure-trademark-filed/.138509|title='Star Twinkle Precure' Trademark Filed|website=Anime News Network|language=en|accessdate=2018-12-27}}</ref> The series is being directed by Hiroaki Miyamoto and written by Isao Murayama, with character design by Akira Takahashi (''[[Suite PreCure]]'' & ''[[Doki Doki! PreCure]]'') and music by [[Yuki Hayashi (composer)|Yuki Hayashi]] (''[[Kirakira PreCure a la Mode]]'' & ''[[Hugtto! PreCure]]'') and Asami Tachibana.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.toei-anim.co.jp/tv/startwinkle_precure/info/|title=\u4f5c\u54c1\u60c5\u5831(\u3055\u304f\u3072\u3093\u3058\u3087\u3046\u307b\u3046) {{!}} \u30b9\u30bf\u30fc\u2606\u30c8\u30a5\u30a4\u30f3\u30af\u30eb\u30d7\u30ea\u30ad\u30e5\u30a2 {{!}} \u6771\u6620\u30a2\u30cb\u30e1\u30fc\u30b7\u30e7\u30f3|website=www.toei-anim.co.jp|language=ja|accessdate=2018-12-27}}</ref><ref name=\"story\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2018-12-26/star-twinkle-precure-anime-unveils-cast-staff-visuals-story/.141337|title=Star \u2606 Twinkle Precure Anime Unveils Cast, Staff, Visuals, Story|website=Anime News Network|language=en|accessdate=2018-12-27}}</ref> The series aired in Japan from February 3, 2019 to January 26, 2020, succeeding the previous series ''Hugtto! PreCure'' in its initial timeslot. In addition, a {{nihongo|PreCure Horoscope|\u30d7\u30ea\u30ad\u30e5\u30a2\u661f\u5ea7\u5360\u3044}} by Arisu Yamada is shown at the end of every episode which features three lucky zodiac signs while in the final episode, Cure Star and Cure Grace tells the viewers that everyone is lucky.\n\n===Music===\n\n==== Opening ====\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!Song\n!Artist\n!Episodes\n|-\n|{{nihongo|'''\"Sparkle\u2606\u5f61Star\u2606Twinkle PreCure\"'''|\u30ad\u30e9\u30ea\u2606\u5f61\u30b9\u30bf\u30fc\u2606\u30c8\u30a5\u30a4\u30f3\u30af\u30eb\u30d7\u30ea\u30ad\u30e5\u30a2}}\n|Rie Kitagawa\n|All\n|}\n\n==== Endings ====\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Song\n!Artist\n!Episodes\n|-\n|{{nihongo|'''\"Papepipu\u2606Romantic\"'''|\u30d1\u307a\u30d4\u30d7\u2606\u30ed\u30de\u30f3\u30c1\u30c3\u30af}}\n|rowspan=2|[[Chihaya Yoshitake]]\n|1 - 5, 9 - 20\n|-\n|{{nihongo|'''\"Please Tell me...! Twinkle!\u2606\"'''|\u6559\u3048\u3066...! \u30c8\u30a5\u30a4\u30f3\u30af\u30eb\u2606}}\n|21 - 34, 39 - 49\n|-\n|{{nihongo|'''\"WINkle! Pretty Cure Miracle Universe\u2606\"'''|WIN\u304f\u308b!\u30d7\u30ea\u30ad\u30e5\u30a2\u30df\u30e9\u30af\u30eb\u30e6\u30cb\u30d0\u30fc\u30b9\u2606}}\n|Rie Kitagawa\n|6 - 8, ''PreCure Miracle Universe''\n|-\n|rowspan=2|'''\"Twinkle Stars\"'''\n|Cure Star (Eimi Naruse), Cure Milky (Konomi Kohara), Cure Soleil (Kiyono Yasuno), Cure Selene (Mikako Komatsu), Cure Cosmo (Sumire Uesaka)\n|35 - 38\n|-\n|[[Rina Chinen]]\n|''Star Twinkle PreCure the Movie: These Feelings Within The Song of Stars''\n|}\n\n==== Insert Songs ====\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Song\n!Artist\n!Episodes\n|-\n|{{nihongo|'''\"Star Color Pendant! Color Charge!\"'''|\u30b9\u30bf\u30fc\u30ab\u30e9\u30fc\u30da\u30f3\u30c0\u30f3\u30c8! \u30ab\u30e9\u30fc\u30c1\u30e3\u30fc\u30b8\uff01}}\n|rowspan=3|Cure Star ([[Eimi Naruse]]), Cure Milky ([[Konomi Kohara]]), Cure Soleil ([[Kiyono Yasuno]]), Cure Selene ([[Mikako Komatsu]]), Cure Cosmo ([[Sumire Uesaka]])\n|All\n|-\n|{{nihongo|'''\"Sparkle\u2606\u5f61Star\u2606Twinkle PreCure\"'''|\u30ad\u30e9\u30ea\u2606\u5f61\u30b9\u30bf\u30fc\u2606\u30c8\u30a5\u30a4\u30f3\u30af\u30eb\u30d7\u30ea\u30ad\u30e5\u30a2}}\n|49\n|-\n|'''\"Twinkle Stars\"'''\n|''Star Twinkle PreCure the Movie: These Feelings Within The Song of Stars''\n|-\n|{{nihongo|'''\"Cosmic\u2606Mystery\u2606Girl\"'''|\u30b3\u30ba\u30df\u30c3\u30af\u2606\u30df\u30b9\u30c6\u30ea\u30fc\u2606\u30ac\u30fc\u30eb}}\n|Cure Cosmo ([[Sumire Uesaka]])\n|15, 23, 24\n|-\n|{{nihongo|'''\"The Constellation's Power\"'''|\u661f\u5ea7\u306e\u30c1\u30ab\u30e9}}\n|[[Chihaya Yoshitake]]\n|''Star Twinkle PreCure the Movie: These Feelings Within The Song of Stars''\n|}\n\n===Films===\nThe characters appear in the theatrical cross-over film {{nihongo|''PreCure Miracle Universe''|\u6620\u753b\u30d7\u30ea\u30ad\u30e5\u30a2\u30df\u30e9\u30af\u30eb\u30e6\u30cb\u30d0\u30fc\u30b9}}, released on March 16, 2019, alongside characters from ''[[Hugtto! PreCure]]'' and ''[[Kirakira PreCure a la Mode]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2018-12-18/toei-outlines-march-precure-miracle-universe-film/.140962|title=Toei Outlines March's Precure Miracle Universe Film|website=Anime News Network|language=en|accessdate=2018-12-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Hodgkins |first1=Crystalyn |title=Precure Miracle Universe Anime Film Reveals Poster Visual |url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/daily-briefs/2018-12-28/precure-miracle-universe-anime-film-reveals-poster-visual/.141399 |website=Anime News Network |accessdate=February 26, 2019 |language=en |date=December 28, 2018}}</ref>\n\nAn anime film titled {{nihongo4|''Star\u2606Twinkle Precure the Movie: These Feelings Within The Song of Stars''|\u6620\u753b\u30b9\u30bf\u30fc\u2606\u30c8\u30a5\u30a4\u30f3\u30af\u30eb\u30d7\u30ea\u30ad\u30e5\u30a2 \u661f\u306e\u6b4c\u306b\u60f3\u3044\u3092\u3053\u3081\u3066|Eiga Sut\u0101 Touinkuru Purikyua Hoshi no Uta ni Omoi wo Komete}} was released on October 19, 2019. Y\u016bta Tanaka is directing the film.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hodgkins |first1=Crystalyn |title=Star \u2606 Twinkle Precure Anime Gets Film on October 19|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2019-06-02/star-twinkle-precure-anime-gets-film-on-october-19/.147388|website=Anime News Network |accessdate=June 2, 2019 |language=en |date=June 2, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Manga===\nA [[manga]] adaptation illustrated by [[Futago Kamikita]] began serialization in [[Kodansha]]'s ''[[Nakayoshi]]'' [[shoujo]] magazine from February 1, 2019.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Ressler |first1=Karen |title=Hugtto! Precure Manga Ends, Star \u2606 Twinkle Precure Manga Begins in February |url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2018-12-30/hugtto-precure-manga-ends-star-twinkle-precure-manga-begins-in-february/.141395 |website=Anime News Network |accessdate=February 26, 2019 |language=en |date=December 30, 2018}}</ref>{{notelist}}\n\n==Reception==\n''Gadget Ts\u016bshin'' listed Hikaru's catchphrase in their 2019 anime buzzwords list.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/interest/2019-12-04/demon-slayer-dr-stone-zombie-land-saga-buzzwords-make-gadget-tsushin-2019-list/.153903|title=Demon Slayer, Dr. Stone, Zombie Land Saga Buzzwords Make Gadget Ts\u016bshin 2019 List|work=[[Anime News Network]]|first1=Lynzee|last1=Loveridge|first2=Kim|last2=Morrissy|date=December 4, 2019|accessdate=December 14, 2019}}</ref>\n\nCosplay marathoner Mitsunobu Saita ran in the 2019 [[Kobe Marathon]] as Cure Cosmo.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.kobe-np.co.jp/news/sougou/201911/0012887784.shtml|title=\u795e\u6238\uff2d\u540d\u7269\u30d7\u30ea\u30ad\u30e5\u30a2\u30e9\u30f3\u30ca\u30fc\u3000\u4eca\u5e74\u306f\u300c\u30ad\u30e5\u30a2\u30b3\u30b9\u30e2\u3060\u30cb\u30e3\u30f3\uff5e\u300d\u3067\u8efd\u3005\u30b5\u30d6\uff13|work=Kobe Shimbun|language=Japanese|date=18 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.toei-anim.co.jp/tv/startwinkle_precure/ Official website] {{in lang|ja}}\n*[http://www.asahi.co.jp/precure/ Official website (Asahi)] {{in lang|ja}}\n*{{ann|anime|21719}}\n\n{{start box}}\n{{succession box\n| title = [[Pretty Cure]]\n| before = [[Hugtto! PreCure]]\n| after = [[Healin' Good PreCure]]\n| years = 2019-2020\n}}\n{{end box}}\n\n{{Pretty Cure}}\n{{Toei Animation}}\n\n[[Category:2019 anime television series]]\n[[Category:Kodansha manga]]\n[[Category:Magical girl anime and manga]]\n[[Category:Pretty Cure]]\n[[Category:Science fiction anime and manga]]\n[[Category:Sh\u014djo manga]]\n[[Category:2019 comics endings]]\n[[Category:Toei Animation television]]\n[[Category:TV Asahi shows]]\n[[Category:Television series about alien visitations]]\n[[Category:Extraterrestrial superheroes]]\n[[Category:Extraterrestrial anime and manga]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox animanga/Header\n| name            = Star Twinkle PreCure\n| image           = Twinkleprecure.jpg\n| image_size      = 250px\n| landscape       = yes\n| caption         = Key visual of the series featuring the five main Cures. From left to right: Cure Cosmo, Cure Milky, Cure Star, Cure Selene and Cure Soleil. Mascots Fuwa and Prunce are visible near the bottom-right and top-left corners respectively. \n| ja_kanji        = \u30b9\u30bf\u30fc\u2606\u30c8\u30a5\u30a4\u30f3\u30af\u30eb\u30d7\u30ea\u30ad\u30e5\u30a2\n| ja_romaji       = Sut\u0101 Touinkuru Purikyua\n| genre           = [[Magical girl]]<!-- Note: Use and cite reliable sources to identify genre/s, not personal interpretation. Please don't include more than three genres (per [[MOS:A&M]]). -->\n}}\n{{Infobox animanga/Video\n| type            = tv series\n| director        = [[jp:\u5bae\u5143\u5b8f\u5f70|Hiroaki Miyamoto]]\n| producer        = Akari Yanagawa\n| writer          = Isao Murayama\n| music           = [[Yuki Hayashi (composer)|Yuki Hayashi]] <br/> Asami Tachibana\n| studio          = [[Toei Animation]]\n| network         = [[All-Nippon News Network|ANN]] ([[Asahi Broadcasting Corporation|ABC]], [[TV Asahi]])\n| first           = February 3, 2019\n| last            = January 26, 2020\n| episodes        = 49\n| episode_list    = List of Star Twinkle PreCure episodes\n}}\n{{Infobox animanga/Print\n| type            = manga\n| author          = [[Izumi Todo]]\n| illustrator     = [[Futago Kamikita]]\n| publisher       = [[Kodansha]]\n| demographic     = ''[[Sh\u014djo manga|Sh\u014djo]]''\n| imprint         = \n| magazine        = [[Nakayoshi]]\n| first           = February 2019\n| last            = December 2019\n| volumes         = 2\n| volume_list     =\n}}\n{{Infobox animanga/Video\n| type            = film\n| title           = Eiga Star\u2606Twinkle PreCure: Hoshi no Uta ni Omoi wo Komete\n| director        = Y\u016bta Tanaka\n| producer        = \n| writer          = Jin Tanaka\n| music           = Yuki Hayashi <br/> Asami Tachibana\n| studio          = Toei Animation\n| licensee        = \n| released        = {{Start date|2019|10|19}}\n| runtime         = \n}}\n{{Infobox animanga/Footer}}\n{{nihongo|'''''Star Twinkle PreCure'''''|\u30b9\u30bf\u30fc\u2606\u30c8\u30a5\u30a4\u30f3\u30af\u30eb\u30d7\u30ea\u30ad\u30e5\u30a2|Sut\u0101 Touinkuru Purikyua|stylized as '''Star\u2606Twinkle PreCure'''}} is a Japanese [[magical girl]] anime series by [[Toei Animation]]. It is the first ''[[Pretty Cure]]'' series released in the [[Reiwa]] period<ref>The series's first 13 episodes were aired during the last days of the [[Heisei]] period, with the [[Reiwa]] Period beginning on May 1, 2019. Despite being aired in the last days in the Heisei period, it was officially recognized as a Reiwa series for consistency.</ref> and the sixteenth installment of the franchise, featuring the fourteenth generation of Cures. It is directed by [[jp:\u5bae\u5143\u5b8f\u5f70|Hiroaki Miyamoto]] (''[[One Piece Film: Gold]]'') and written by Isao Murayama. The series aired on all [[All-Nippon News Network|ANN]] stations in Japan from February 3, 2019 to January 26, 2020, succeeding ''[[Hugtto! PreCure]]'' in its initial time slot.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.toei-anim.co.jp/tv/startwinkle_precure/|title=\u30b9\u30bf\u30fc\u2606\u30c8\u30a5\u30a4\u30f3\u30af\u30eb\u30d7\u30ea\u30ad\u30e5\u30a2 {{!}} \u6771\u6620\u30a2\u30cb\u30e1\u30fc\u30b7\u30e7\u30f3|website=www.toei-anim.co.jp|language=ja|accessdate=2018-12-27}}</ref> It was then succeeded by ''[[Healin' Good PreCure]]'' on February 2, 2020. The series' main topic is [[imagination]], with [[outer space]] and [[constellations]] being the Cures' main motifs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cinematoday.jp/news/N0105869|title=\u53f2\u4e0a\u521d\u30fb\u5b87\u5b99\u4eba\u30d7\u30ea\u30ad\u30e5\u30a2\u767b\u5834\uff01\u3067\u3093\u3071\u7d44.inc\u6210\u702c\u745b\u7f8e\u3089\u300c\u30b9\u30bf\u30fc\u2606\u30c8\u30a5\u30a4\u30f3\u30af\u30eb\u30d7\u30ea\u30ad\u30e5\u30a2\u300d\u58f0\u512a\u767a\u8868|website=\u30b7\u30cd\u30de\u30c8\u30a5\u30c7\u30a4|accessdate=2018-12-27}}</ref>\n\n==Story==\nThe {{nihongo|Starry Sky World|\u661f\u7a7a\u754c|Hoshizora-kai}} is the home to the twelve Star Princesses who are based on the [[Zodiac signs]] and maintain order in the universe. But when the Notraiders attack the Star Palace, the princesses scatter themselves across the universe as the Princess Star Color Pens. Seeking to revive the princesses and avert the universe from being consumed in darkness, the aliens Lala and Prunce travel with the fairy Fuwa to {{nihongo|Mihoshi Town|\u89b3\u661f\u753a|Mihoshi-ch\u014d}} on Earth where they meet the imaginative Hikaru Hoshina. Receiving a Star Color Pendant and one of the Star Color Pens, Hikaru transforms into the legendary PreCure, Cure Star. Joined by Lala and two other girls, Elena and Madoka, as well as the shapeshifting cat-like alien, Yuni, Hikaru leads the Star Twinkle PreCure as they seek to revive the Star Princesses and fight against the Notraiders.<ref name=\"story\"/>\n\n==Characters==\nThe titular characters are a team of magical girls who use the rocket ship that Lala came to Earth in to travel through space. They derive their powers from the Star Color Pendant and {{nihongo|Star Color Pens|\u30b9\u30bf\u30fc\u30ab\u30e9\u30fc\u30da\u30f3|Sut\u0101 Kar\u0101 Pen}}, tasked to collect the twelve {{nihongo|Princess Star Color Pens|\u30d7\u30ea\u30f3\u30bb\u30b9\u30b9\u30bf\u30fc\u30ab\u30e9\u30fc\u30da\u30f3|Purinsesu Sut\u0101 Kar\u0101 Pen}} needed for their mission to revive the Star Princesses.\n<!-- Remember to keep the names in Western order outside the Nihongo romanization -->\n;{{nihongo|Hikaru Hoshina|\u661f\u5948 \u3072\u304b\u308b|Hoshina Hikaru|extra2=/}} {{nihongo|Cure Star|\u30ad\u30e5\u30a2\u30b9\u30bf\u30fc|Kyua Sut\u0101}}<ref name=\":0\"/>\n:{{Voiced by|[[Eimi Naruse]]}}\n:A second year middle school girl who loves [[stars]] and constellations. She is cheerful and full of imagination, but also stubborn and often acts on intuition. She enjoys looking at the stars and writing in her notebook, which has turned into the \"Twinkle Book.\" As the [[pink]]-colored Cure Star, whose motif is stars, her main technique is \"Star Punch\" which can be upgraded into stronger variations by using a Princess Star Color Pen. In the last episode, Hikaru became an astronaut just like she promised Lala.\n;{{nihongo|Lala Hagoromo|\u7fbd\u8863 \u30e9\u30e9|Hagoromo Rara|extra2=/}} {{nihongo|Cure Milky|\u30ad\u30e5\u30a2\u30df\u30eb\u30ad\u30fc|Kyua Miruk\u012b}}<ref name=\":0\"/>\n:{{Voiced by|[[Konomi Kohara]]}}\n:The first alien to become a Pretty Cure,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.oricon.co.jp/news/2129237/full/|title=\u300e\u30d7\u30ea\u30ad\u30e5\u30a2\u300f\u30b7\u30ea\u30fc\u30ba\u521d\u306e\u5b87\u5b99\u4eba\u30d7\u30ea\u30ad\u30e5\u30a2\u8a95\u751f \u5929\u306e\u5ddd\u306e\u30d7\u30ea\u30ad\u30e5\u30a2\u30fb\u30ad\u30e5\u30a2\u30df\u30eb\u30ad\u30fc|website=[[Oricon News]]|language=ja|accessdate=August 23, 2019}}</ref> Lala is from the planet {{nihongo|Samaan|\u30b5\u30de\u30fc\u30f3|Sam\u0101n}} who came with Prunce and Fuwa to find the Precure on Earth and ends up becoming one herself. While her presence on Earth is considered illegal according to space laws, she is allowed to remain on Earth under an alias. While serious and responsible, she sometimes makes mistakes while having trouble getting accustomed to Earth's people and customs. As the [[Teal (color)|teal]]-colored Cure Milky, whose motif is the [[Milky Way]] and hearts, her main technique is \"Milky Shock\" which can be upgraded into stronger variations by using a Princess Star Color Pen. In the last episode, Lala became a doctor of the A.I.\n;{{nihongo|Elena Amamiya|\u5929\u5bae \u3048\u308c\u306a|Amamiya Erena|extra2=/}} {{nihongo|Cure Soleil|\u30ad\u30e5\u30a2\u30bd\u30ec\u30a4\u30e6|Kyua Soreiyu}}<ref name=\":0\"/>\n:{{Voiced by|[[Kiyono Yasuno]]}}\n:A popular third year middle school student with a radiant smile and athletic prowess, referred to as the \"Sun of Mihoshi Town.\" A [[h\u0101fu]] who is [[Mexicans|Mexican]] on her father's side, her family own the Sonrisa Flower shop where she works part time while looking after her younger siblings. As the [[yellow]] and [[Orange (colour)|orange]]-colored Cure Soleil, whose motif is the [[sun]], her main technique is \"Soleil Shoot\" which can be upgraded into stronger variations by using a Princess Star Color Pen. In the last episode, Elena became a tv interpreter for the media coverage.\n;{{nihongo|Madoka Kaguya|\u9999\u4e45\u77e2 \u307e\u3069\u304b|Kaguya Madoka|extra2=/}} {{nihongo|Cure Selene|\u30ad\u30e5\u30a2\u30bb\u30ec\u30fc\u30cd|Kyua Ser\u0113ne}}<ref name=\":0\"/>\n:{{Voiced by|[[Mikako Komatsu]]}}\n:A third year middle school student who is the student council president of Hikaru's school, referred to as the \"Moon of Mihoshi Town\". Her father works for the government, and her mother is a pianist. She often strives to be ladylike and is sweet, but can be blunt at times. She is multi-talented in archery, piano, and flower arrangements. As the [[purple]]-colored Cure Selene, whose motif is the [[moon]], her main technique is \"Selene Arrow\" which can be upgraded into stronger variations by using a Princess Star Color Pen. In the last episode, Madoka took her dad's job as the Space Investigator.\n;{{nihongo|Yuni|\u30e6\u30cb|Yuni|extra2=/}} {{nihongo|Cure Cosmo|\u30ad\u30e5\u30a2\u30b3\u30b9\u30e2|Kyua Kosumo}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.toei-anim.co.jp/tv/startwinkle_precure/news/2019053101.php|title=\u4e0a\u5742\u3046\u3048\u3055\u304b\u3059\u307f\u308c\uff08\u30de\u30aa\uff0f\u30d6\u30eb\u30fc\u30ad\u30e3\u30c3\u30c8\uff0f\u30ad\u30e5\u30a2\u30b3\u30b9\u30e2\u5f79\uff09}}</ref>\n:{{Voiced by|[[Sumire Uesaka]]}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.toei-anim.co.jp/tv/startwinkle_precure/news/2019051101.php|title=\u4e0a\u5742\u3059\u307f\u308c\uff08\u30de\u30aa\u5f79\uff09}}</ref> \n:A shapeshifting [[Catgirl (anime and manga)|catgirl]] from the Planet Rainbow whose people were turned into stone as the result of Aiwarn's experiments. Using a perfume to assist with her shapeshifting, with her ears and tail always remaining, Yuni has searched for a way to restore her people by assuming the identities of phantom thief {{nihongo|Blue Cat|\u30d6\u30eb\u30fc\u30ad\u30e3\u30c3\u30c8|Bur\u016b Kyatto}} to steal stolen treasures, the intergalactic pop idol {{nihongo|Mao|\u30de\u30aa|Mao}} to gather information, and Aiwarn's butler assistant {{nihongo|Bakenyan|\u30d0\u30b1\u30cb\u30e3\u30fc\u30f3|Bakeny\u0101n}} ({{Voiced by|[[Y\u014dji Ueda]]}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.toei-anim.co.jp/tv/startwinkle_precure/news/2019030901.php|title=\u4e0a\u7530 \u71ff\u53f8\uff08\u30d0\u30b1\u30cb\u30e3\u30fc\u30f3 \u5f79\uff09}}</ref>) to infiltrate the Notraiders. After becoming a Precure, Yuni joins Hikaru and the others to search for the pens with them. As the [[blue]] and [[rainbow]]-colored Cure Cosmo, whose motif is the [[rainbow]], she is armed with the Rainbow Perfume which she uses in her \"Cosmo Shining\" technique with its \"Rainbow Splash\" variation using a Princess Star Color Pen. In the last episode, Yuni is seen with Olyfio as they watch Hikaru being launched into space.\n\n===Starry Sky World===\n;{{nihongo|Fuwa|\u30d5\u30ef}}<ref name=\":0\"/>\n:{{Voiced by|[[Hina Kino]]}}\n: A baby fairy with the power to create portals through space who was created by the Star Princesses as both a means of reviving them and stopping Ophiuchus, normally residing in the Twinkle Book. After the Star Princess Pens have been gathered, Fuwa is transformed into a unicorn-like fairy with the PreCure told to help her reach her full potential by acquiring their Twinkle Imagination as part of the Star Princesses' plan to destroy Ophiuchus. Despite learning that absorbing the Cures' Twinkle Imagination would ultimately destroy her as well in the process, Fuwa proceeds in the attempt to eliminate Ophiuchus and fails. Fuwa is later revived after the Cures defeated Ophiuchus, but lost her memories and powers.\n;{{nihongo|Prunce|\u30d7\u30eb\u30f3\u30b9|Purunsu}}<ref name=\":0\"/>\n:{{voiced by|[[Hiroyuki Yoshino]]}}\n: An UFO-like alien who serves the Star Princesses and came to Earth with Lala to seek the PreCure.\n;{{nihongo|AI|\u3048\u30fc\u3042\u3044}}\n:{{Voiced by|[[Miki It\u014d]]}}\n: The [[artificial intelligence]] system of the rocket.\n;{{nihongo|Abraham|\u30a2\u30d6\u30e9\u30cf\u30e0|Aburahamu}}\n:{{Voiced by|[[Yutaka Aoyama]]}}\n:An alien from Planet Minitur who assumed a form of a film director so he can test the Precure's determination to have Lala stay on Earth.\n\n====Star Princesses====\nThe {{nihongo|'''Star Princesses'''|\u30b9\u30bf\u30fc\u30d7\u30ea\u30f3\u30bb\u30b9|Sut\u0101 Purinsesu}} are thirteen princesses who protect the balance of the universe, with Ophiuchus originally a member before she turned her back on them when they decided to transfer half of their power to bestow all life in the universe with imagination. The Star Princesses used the rest of their power to create Fuwa and used their remaining strength to drive the Notraiders away, which scatter across the universe as the Princess Star Color Pens sought by the Precure and the Notraiders. Each princess represents one of the 12 Zodiac signs.\n\n;{{nihongo|Taurus|\u304a\u3046\u3057\u5ea7|Oushi-za}}\n:{{Voiced by|[[Ayako Kawasumi]]}}\n:The Star Princess based on [[Taurus (constellation)|Taurus]], whose pink Princess Star Color Pen was found on Earth.\n;{{nihongo|Leo|\u3057\u3057\u5ea7|Shishi-za}}\n:{{Voiced by|[[Madoka Yonezawa]]}}\n:The Star Princess based on [[Leo (constellation)|Leo]], whose cyan Princess Star Color Pen was found on Earth.\n;{{nihongo|Libra|\u3066\u3093\u3073\u3093\u5ea7|Tenbin-za}}\n:{{Voiced by|[[Mako (voice actress)|Mako]]}}\n:The Star Princess based on [[Libra (constellation)|Libra]], whose yellow Princess Star Color Pen with found on Planet Kennel.\n;{{nihongo|Capricorn|\u3084\u304e\u5ea7|Yagi-za}}\n:{{Voiced by|[[Marika Hayashi]]}}\n:The Star Princess based on [[Capricornus (constellation)|Capricornus]], whose magenta Princess Star Color Pen was in the Notraiders' possession before the Precure took it.\n;{{nihongo|Scorpio|\u3055\u305d\u308a\u5ea7|Sasori-za}}\n:{{Voiced by|Unknown}}\n:The Star Princess based on [[Scorpius (constellation)|Scorpius]], whose orange Princess Star Color Pen was in the Notraiders' possession before the Precure took it.\n;{{nihongo|Sagittarius|\u3044\u3066\u5ea7|Ite-za}}\n:{{Voiced by|Unknown}}\n:The Star Princess based on [[Sagittarius (constellation)|Sagittarius]], whose lilac Princess Star Color Pen was found on planet Zeni.\n;{{nihongo|Virgo|\u304a\u3068\u3081\u5ea7|Otome-za}}\n:{{Voiced by|Unknown}}\n:The Star Princess based on [[Virgo (constellation)|Virgo]], whose white Princess Star Color Pen was found on planet Zeni.\n;{{nihongo|Gemini|\u3075\u305f\u3054\u5ea7|Futago-za}}\n:{{Voiced by|Unknown}}\n:Star Princess twin sisters based on [[Gemini (constellation)|Gemini]], whose teal Princess Star Color Pen was found on planet Rainbow.\n;{{nihongo|Aries|\u304a\u3072\u3064\u3058\u5ea7|Ohitsuji-za}}\n:{{Voiced by|Unknown}}\n:The Star Princess based on [[Aries (constellation)|Aries]], whose red Princess Star Color Pen was found on planet Kumarin.\n;{{nihongo|Aquarius|\u307f\u305a\u304c\u3081\u5ea7|Mizugame-za}}\n:{{Voiced by|Unknown}}\n:The Star Princess based on [[Aquarius (constellation)|Aquarius]], whose blue Princess Star Color Pen was found on planet Icesnow.\n;{{nihongo|Cancer|\u304b\u306b\u5ea7|Kani-za}}\n:{{Voiced by|Unknown}}\n:The Star Princess based on [[Cancer (constellation)|Cancer]], whose green Princess Star Color Pen was found on planet Saman.\n;{{nihongo|Pisces|\u3046\u304a\u5ea7|Uo-za}}\n:{{Voiced by|Unknown}}\n:The Star Princess based on [[Pisces (constellation)|Pisces]], whose light pink Princess Star Color Pen was found somewhere floating in space.\n\n===Notraiders===\nThe {{nihongo|'''Notraiders'''|\u30ce\u30c3\u30c8\u30ec\u30a4\u30c0\u30fc|Nottoreid\u0101}}, the main antagonists of the series, who originate from the darkest and forgotten parts of the universe, are an intergalactic army of space raiders seeking universal dominion by obtaining all the Princess Star Color Pens to purge the universe of all light and give its power to their leader. Later, they seek to capture Fuwa as a vessel. Their leading members are based on the [[Y\u014dkai|yokai]] from [[Japanese mythology]]. The name \"Notto\" means take over (\u4e57\u3063\u53d6\u308b).\n\n====Leaders====\n;{{nihongo|Darknest / Ophiuchus|\u30c0\u30fc\u30af\u30cd\u30b9\u30c8 / \u3078\u3073\u3064\u304b\u3044\u5ea7|D\u0101kunesuto / Hebitsukai-Za}}\n:{{Voiced by|[[Mie Sonozaki]]}}<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.animatetimes.com/news/details.php?id=1578131411|title=\u300e\u30b9\u30bf\u30fc\u2606\u30c8\u30a5\u30a4\u30f3\u30af\u30eb\u30d7\u30ea\u30ad\u30e5\u30a2\u300f\u30c0\u30fc\u30af\u30cd\u30b9\u30c8\u306e\u6b63\u4f53\u304c\u5224\u660e\uff01\u3000\u6f14\u3058\u308b\u306e\u306f\u58f0\u512a\u30fb\u5712\u5d0e\u672a\u6075\u3055\u3093\u3001\u71b1\u3044\u60f3\u3044\u306e\u30b3\u30e1\u30f3\u30c8\u3082\u5927\u516c\u958b}}</ref>\n:Leader of the Notraiders and the primary antagonist of the series, [[Ophiuchus]] is actually a former member of the Star Princesses who became disillusioned with the universe they created when her fellow princesses voted against her to bestow half of their collective power to all life in the form of imagination. This influenced her to turn on her fellow princesses before they exiled her, eventually regaining her strength and assuming the identity of Darknest, a snake-armored figure with an Uwabami-like serpent wrapped around her body, to consume all light in the universe. But Ophiuchus eventually discards her disguise and minions, capturing Fuwa and the Star Princesses to conduct a ritual to unmake the universe. After surviving the Star Princesses's gambit to destroy her through Fuwa, Ophiuchus is ultimately defeated by the Precures and accepts her loss while vowing to return if things become twisted again.\n\n;{{nihongo|Garuouga|\u30ac\u30eb\u30aa\u30a6\u30ac|Garuouga}}\n:{{Voiced by|Satoshi Tsuruoka}}<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.toei-anim.co.jp/tv/startwinkle_precure/news/2019022301.php|title=\u9db4\u5ca1 \u8061\uff08\u30ac\u30eb\u30aa\u30a6\u30ac \u5f79\uff09}}</ref>\n:Second-in command of the Notraiders, he is an [[oni]]-like alien who became Darknest's follower after his planet was destroyed with the promise of power. His bracelet can also increase the commanders' powers and has a powerful physical strength to inflict damage on his opponents. During his final battle, he battles the Cures until learning of Darknest's identity as Ophiuchus and she destroyed the world. Garouoga attempts to kill Ophiuchus before she places him and the commanders under her control by twisting their imagination, the Cures purify them before Aiwarn takes them to safety.\n\n====Commanders====\nGaruouga's subordinates who aid in reviving Darknest, each using different method to battle the Pretty Cures to hinder their mission. Garuouga later increase their powers, with Darknest upgrading their abilities further.\n;{{nihongo|Kappard|\u30ab\u30c3\u30d1\u30fc\u30c9|Kapp\u0101do}}\n:{{Voiced by|[[Yoshimasa Hosoya]]}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.toei-anim.co.jp/tv/startwinkle_precure/news/2019020201.php|title=\u7d30\u8c37\u4f73\u6b63\uff08\u30ab\u30c3\u30d1\u30fc\u30c9 \u5f79\uff09}}</ref>\n: A [[Kappa (folklore)|kappa]]-like Commander armed with a [[lightsaber]]-like dual blade he uses in his \"Kappard Strike\" attack, originating from a planet that was destroyed as the result of its na\u00efve people being exploited by other races. This motivated Kappard to believe that peoples from other worlds are incapable of coexisting with each other. While initially seeking to capture Fuwa by any means, he is also a warrior who considers the Pretty Cures as worthy opponents. When empowered by Darknest, his blade can now take peoples' imagination and take the form of other weapons. Given a final chance, he confront Hikaru by using his own imagination to further power up his weapon and overpower her first, the Cures manage to defeat him but Darknest teleport him back and absorb him, empower him. During his final battle, he clash with the Cures until he discover Darknest's identity as Ophiuchus, the enraged Kappard attempt to kill her with his allies but she put them under her control by twisting their imagination, the Cures purify them before Aiwarn take them safety.\n;{{nihongo|Tenjou|\u30c6\u30f3\u30b8\u30e7\u30a6|Tenj\u014d}}\n:{{Voiced by|[[Aya End\u014d]]}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.toei-anim.co.jp/tv/startwinkle_precure/news/2019020901.php|title=\u9060\u85e4\u7dbe\uff08\u30c6\u30f3\u30b8\u30e7\u30a6 \u5f79\uff09}}</ref>\n: A playful [[tengu]]-like Commander armed with a fan who originated from Planet Guten, joining the Notraiders over her feelings of being an outcast due to her small nose. Tenjou strategizes her attacks on the Pretty Cures, though she is more interested in the Star Princesses' power than capturing Fuwa. She often use Notrei as [[Human chess]] pieces to fight the Cures, her upgrade by Darknest allowing her to seal a person inside a Nottorei to enhance grunt via their imagination in size and power. In episode 39, 42 and 43, she has rivalry with Elena because they have the same past. When she attack her homeland, Elena understand her feelings and attempt to reconcile with her but she refused. During her final battle, she clash with the Cures until she discover Darknest's identity as Ophiuchus, the enraged Tenjou attempt to kill her with his allies but she put them under her control by twisting their imagination, the Cures purify them before Aiwarn take them safety.\n;{{nihongo|Aiwarn|\u30a2\u30a4\u30ef\u30fc\u30f3|Aiw\u0101n}}\n:{{Voiced by|[[Rie Murakawa]]}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.toei-anim.co.jp/tv/startwinkle_precure/news/2019022301.php|title=\u6751\u5ddd \u68a8\u8863\uff08\u30a2\u30a4\u30ef\u30fc\u30f3 \u5f79\uff09}}</ref>\n: A bratty [[Hitotsume-koz\u014d]]-like Commander armed with a laser pistol who sees others as subjects in her experiments, having petrified the denizens of planet Rainbow to develop the means of corrupting the Princess Star Color Pens into {{nihongo|Dark Pens|\u30c0\u30fc\u30af\u30da\u30f3|D\u0101ku Pen}}. Aiwarn uses the Dark Pens to create Notriggers from her targets' imaginations, the monsters' strength boosted whenever Aiwarn is enhanced by Darknest. Following the revelation that Bakenyan is one of Yuni's disguises, Aiwarn sought revenge on her for being kicked out of the Notraiders while modifying Yuni's spaceship into her personal transforming robot Aiwarn Robo Unit 16. She makes numerous attempts on Yuni's life until she was stopped from petrifying Planet Uranei's residents, with Yuni apologizing to Aiwarn once realizing she had no home other than with the Notraiders. Aiwarn takes her leave after declining Yuni's offer to live on Earth with her and the other Cures. During the final battle, she aids the Cures against her former allies while returning the favor to Yuni by apologizing back to her about how she reacted to Yuni.\n\n====Grunts====\n;{{nihongo|Notrei|\u30ce\u30c3\u30c8\u30ec\u30a4|Nottorei}}\n:{{Voiced by|[[Yoshimitsu Shimoyama]], Kenta Tanaka, Kosuke Echigoya, Yu Miyazaki, Yui Kondo, Sachiko Kojima and Kim Hyang-ri}}\n: The foot-soldiers of the Notraiders who are armed with laser blasters. They later become Tenjou's personal monster after receiving powers from Darknest, which she use peoples' imagination to turn them into giant version of Notrei.\n;{{nihongo|Notrigger|\u30ce\u30c3\u30c8\u30ea\u30ac\u30fc|Nottorig\u0101}}\n:{{Voiced by|Yoshimitsu Shimoyama}}\n: Aiwarn's personal monsters that she creates using a Dark Pen, each Notrigger's form being based on a random object or strong desire from a targeted person's imagination which Aiwarn uses the pen on.\n\n===Hoshina family===\n;{{nihongo|Harukichi Hoshina|\u661f\u5948 \u6625\u5409|Hoshina Harukichi}}\n:{{Voiced by|[[Mitsuru Ogata]]}}\n:Hikaru's grandfather, who has strict rules around the house.\n;{{nihongo|Terumi Hoshina|\u661f\u5948 \u8f1d\u7f8e|Hoshina Terumi}}\n:{{Voiced by|[[Sachiko Kojima]]}}\n:Hikaru's mother, who is a ''[[mangaka]]''.\n;{{nihongo|Yoko Hoshina|\u661f\u5948 \u967d\u5b50|Hoshina Y\u014dko}}\n:{{Voiced by|[[Y\u014dko Asagami]]}}\n:Hikaru's grandmother.\n;{{nihongo|Yoichi Hoshina|\u661f\u5948 \u967d\u4e00|Hoshina Y\u014dichi}}\n:{{Voiced by|[[Akio \u014ctsuka]]}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.toei-anim.co.jp/tv/startwinkle_precure/news/2019070601.php|title=\u5927\u585a \u660e\u592b \uff08\u661f\u5948 \u967d\u4e00\u5f79\uff09}}</ref> \n:Hikaru's father, who works overseas [[Ufology|studying aliens]] and other [[Cryptozoology|cryptids]].\n;{{nihongo|Yeti|\u30a4\u30a8\u30c6\u30a3|Ieti}}\n:{{Voiced by|[[Y\u014dhei Tadano]]}}\n:Hikaru's pet dog.\n\n===Lala's family===\n;{{nihongo|Toto|\u30c8\u30c8|Toto}}\n:{{Voiced by|[[Toshihiko Seki]]}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.toei-anim.co.jp/tv/startwinkle_precure/news/2019082401.php|title=\u95a2 \u4fca\u5f66\uff08\u30c8\u30c8\u5f79\uff09}}</ref>\n:Lala's father, who is an AI Researcher.\n;{{nihongo|Kaka|\u30ab\u30ab|Kaka}}\n:{{Voiced by|[[Fumi Hirano]]}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.toei-anim.co.jp/tv/startwinkle_precure/news/2019082401.php|title=\u5e73\u91ce \u6587\uff08\u30ab\u30ab\u5f79\uff09}}</ref>\n:Lala's mother, who is a Doctor of Rocket Engineering.\n;{{nihongo|Lolo|\u30ed\u30ed|Roro}}\n:{{Voiced by|[[S\u014dma Sait\u014d]]}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.crunchyroll.com/en-gb/anime-news/2019/08/04/danmachi-star-soma-saito-joins-cast-of-star-twinkle-precure|title=DanMachi Star Soma Saito Joins Cast of Star Twinkle PreCure}}</ref>\n:Lala's older twin brother.\n\n=== Amamiya family ===\n;{{nihongo|Carlos|\u30ab\u30eb\u30ed\u30b9|Karurosu}}\n:{{Voiced by|Kentaro Tone}}\n:Elena's father, who is Mexican and the owner of Sonrisa.\n;{{nihongo|Kaede Amamiya|\u5929\u5bae \u304b\u3048\u3067|Amamiya Kaede}}\n:{{Voiced by|[[Ayahi Takagaki]]}}\n:Elena's mother, who is Japanese and an interpreter.\n;{{nihongo|Toma Amamiya|\u5929\u5bae \u3068\u3046\u307e|Amamiya T\u014dma}}, {{nihongo|Reina Amamiya|\u5929\u5bae \u308c\u3044\u306a|Amamiya Reina}}, {{nihongo|Takuto Amamiya|\u5929\u5bae \u305f\u304f\u3068|Amamiya Takuto}}, {{nihongo|Ikuto Amamiya|\u5929\u5bae \u3044\u304f\u3068|Amamiya Ikuto}}, {{nihongo|Anna Amamiya|\u5929\u5bae \u3042\u3093\u306a|Amamiya Anna}}\n:{{Voiced by|Yui Kondo, Mai Nishikawa, [[Healin%27_Good_PreCure#Pretty_Cures|Natsu Yorita]], [[Anzu Haruno]]}}\n:Elena's siblings.\n\n===Kaguya family===\n;{{nihongo|Fuyuki Kaguya|\u9999\u4e45\u77e2 \u51ac\u8cb4|Kaguya Fuyuki}}\n:{{Voiced by|[[Ken Narita]]}}\n:Madoka's stern father who works at the government, perceiving aliens as threat while forbidding his family from keeping secrets.\n;{{nihongo|Mitsuka Kaguya|\u9999\u4e45\u77e2 \u6e80\u4f73|Kaguya Mitsuka}}\n:{{Voiced by|[[Hekiru Shiina]]}}\n:Madoka's mother, who was a famous pianist.\n\n===Yuni's family===\n;{{nihongo|Olyfio|\u30aa\u30ea\u30fc\u30d5\u30a3\u30aa|Or\u012bfio}}\n:{{Voiced by|[[K\u014dki Miyata]]}}\n:The queen of Planet Rainbow.\n\n===Others===\n;{{nihongo|Drams|\u30c9\u30e9\u30e0\u30b9|Doramusu}}\n:{{Voiced by|[[Subaru Kimura]]}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.toei-anim.co.jp/tv/startwinkle_precure/news/2019051101.php|title=\u6728\u6751 \u6634\uff08\u30c9\u30e9\u30e0\u30b9\u5f79\uff09}}</ref>\n:A dragon-like alien from the planet Zeni.\n\n;{{nihongo|Yanyan|\u30e4\u30f3\u30e4\u30f3|Yanyan}}\n:{{Voiced by|[[Asuka Nishi]]}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.toei-anim.co.jp/tv/startwinkle_precure/character/chara9.php|title=\u3068\u308a\u307e\u304f\u4eba\u3005 \u7570\u661f\u4eba {{!}} \u30b9\u30bf\u30fc\u2606\u30c8\u30a5\u30a4\u30f3\u30af\u30eb\u30d7\u30ea\u30ad\u30e5\u30a2 {{!}} \u6771\u6620\u30a2\u30cb\u30e1\u30fc\u30b7\u30e7\u30f3|website=www.toei-anim.co.jp|language=ja|access-date=2019-08-05}}</ref>\n:A hitchhiking [[hermit crab]] alien with a yellow bucket on her back from the planet Pururun.\n\n;{{nihongo|Tatsunori Karube|\u30ab\u30eb\u30d9\u30bf\u30c4\u30ce\u30ea|Karube Tatsunori}}\n:{{Voiced by|[[Junya Enoki]]}}\n:Tatsunori is a classmate.\n\n;{{nihongo|Sakurako Himenojo|\u30d2\u30e1\u30ce\u30b8\u30e7\u3055\u304f\u3089\u3053|Himenoj\u014d Sakurako}}\n:{{Voiced by|[[Y\u014d Taichi]]}}\n:Madoka's classmate.\n\n;{{nihongo|Yumika Nasu|\u30ca\u30b9\u30e6\u30df\u30ab|Nasu Yumika}}\n:{{Voiced by|Makoto Koichi}}\n:Madoka's good friend.\n\n;{{nihongo|Nodoka Hanadera|\u82b1\u5bfa\u306e\u3069\u304b|Hanadera Nodoka}} / {{nihongo|Cure Grace|\u30ad\u30e5\u30a2\u30b0\u30ec\u30fc\u30b9|Kyua Gur\u0113su}}\n:{{anime voice|[[Aoi Y\u016bki]]}}\n:A girl who is the pink-colored Pretty Cure of Flowers from ''[[Healin' Good PreCure]]''.\n\n;{{nihongo|Latte|\u30e9\u30c6|Rate}}\n:{{anime voice|[[Haruka Shiraishi]]}}\n:A brown dog-like fairy from ''Healin' Good PreCure'' who is the {{nihongo|Young Princess of the Healing Garden|\u30d2\u30fc\u30ea\u30f3\u30b0\u30ac\u30fc\u30c7\u30f3\u306e\u5e7c\u3044\u738b\u5973\u3055\u307e}}\n\n===Film only characters===\n;{{nihongo|Piton|\u30d4\u30c8\u30f3|Piton}}\n:{{Voiced by|[[Etsuko Kozakura]]}}\n:A chick-like alien from Planet Miracle. He was good at developing Miracle Lights. He was framed by Yango that caused the malfunction of the factory and seek the Cures to help him clear his name. After Yango's defeat he was appointed as a maker of Miracle Lights.\n;{{nihongo|Yango|\u30e4\u30f3\u30b4|Yango}}\n:{{Voiced by|[[Y\u016bki Kaji]]}}\n:A manipulative and deceptive crow-like alien from Planet Miracle who serves as the main antagonist in ''Precure Miracle Universe''. Working for the president to end the threat around the universe. He was sent to bring Piton and the Cures in because he believe they are responsible for the disappearance of the Miracle light. It was revealed that he caused the malfunction of the factory to frame Piton. The Cures then help Piton expose his corruption and they gather their feelings to purify him, expelling the darkness inside him. \n;{{nihongo|President|\u5927\u7d71\u9818|Dait\u014dry\u014d}}\n:{{Voiced by|[[Yuji Tanaka]]}}\n:An owl-like alien and head of the Planet Miracle.\n;{{nihongo|UMA|\u30e6\u30fc\u30de|Y\u016bma}}\n:A star-like alien that sing, but do not speak and labelled as \"Star Drop\". She befriend the Cures before the alien hunters targets her for bounty. When Burn attempt to capture her, she goes berserk and consumes the planet. Hikaru and Lala's song were able to reach her and she disappeared.\n;{{nihongo|Mary Anne|\u30e1\u30ea\u30fc\u30fb\u30a2\u30f3|Mer\u012b An}}\n:{{Voiced by|[[Rina Chinen]]}}\n:A dog-like alien who is a Starry Sky police detective, instructed to arrest Yuni. She can be a little over the top at times.\n;{{nihongo|Gyro III, Hydro, Burn, Dive, Chop|\u30b8\u30e3\u30a4\u30edIII, \u30cf\u30a4\u30c9\u30ed, \u30d0\u30fc\u30f3, \u30c0\u30a4\u30d6, \u30c1\u30e7\u30c3\u30d7|Jairo III, Haidoro, B\u0101n, Daibu, Choppu}}\n:{{Voiced by|Takayuki Hamatsu, [[Yui Ishikawa]], [[Shunsuke Sakuya]], [[Jin Katagiri]], and Ry\u016bsuke Komakine<ref>https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2019-09-04/star-twinkle-precure-anime-film-reveals-guest-cast-for-5-alien-hunters/.150706</ref>}}\n:A gang of five alien hunters targeting the UMA. They are the main antagonists of the movie. They invade Earth to capture UMA to collect a bounty but were confronted by the Cures, the girls were able to defeat them but Burn attemp to capture UMA which caused her to go berserk. After UMA's departure, the hunters are all incarcerated.\n\n==Media==\n\n===Anime===\n{{see also|List of Star Twinkle PreCure episodes}}\n'' Star Twinkle PreCure'' was announced on November 28, 2018,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2018-11-28/toei-confirms-star-twinkle-precure-tv-anime-for-2019/.140086|title=Toei Confirms Star Twinkle Precure TV Anime for 2019|website=Anime News Network|language=en|accessdate=2018-12-27}}</ref> following a trademark filing reported on October 5, 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/daily-briefs/2018-10-23/star-twinkle-precure-trademark-filed/.138509|title='Star Twinkle Precure' Trademark Filed|website=Anime News Network|language=en|accessdate=2018-12-27}}</ref> The series is being directed by Hiroaki Miyamoto and written by Isao Murayama, with character design by Akira Takahashi (''[[Suite PreCure]]'' & ''[[Doki Doki! PreCure]]'') and music by [[Yuki Hayashi (composer)|Yuki Hayashi]] (''[[Kirakira PreCure a la Mode]]'' & ''[[Hugtto! PreCure]]'') and Asami Tachibana.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.toei-anim.co.jp/tv/startwinkle_precure/info/|title=\u4f5c\u54c1\u60c5\u5831(\u3055\u304f\u3072\u3093\u3058\u3087\u3046\u307b\u3046) {{!}} \u30b9\u30bf\u30fc\u2606\u30c8\u30a5\u30a4\u30f3\u30af\u30eb\u30d7\u30ea\u30ad\u30e5\u30a2 {{!}} \u6771\u6620\u30a2\u30cb\u30e1\u30fc\u30b7\u30e7\u30f3|website=www.toei-anim.co.jp|language=ja|accessdate=2018-12-27}}</ref><ref name=\"story\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2018-12-26/star-twinkle-precure-anime-unveils-cast-staff-visuals-story/.141337|title=Star \u2606 Twinkle Precure Anime Unveils Cast, Staff, Visuals, Story|website=Anime News Network|language=en|accessdate=2018-12-27}}</ref> The series aired in Japan from February 3, 2019 to January 26, 2020, succeeding the previous series ''Hugtto! PreCure'' in its initial timeslot. In addition, a {{nihongo|PreCure Horoscope|\u30d7\u30ea\u30ad\u30e5\u30a2\u661f\u5ea7\u5360\u3044}} by Arisu Yamada is shown at the end of every episode which features three lucky zodiac signs while in the final episode, Cure Star and Cure Grace tells the viewers that everyone is lucky. The first official soundtrack, titled {{nihongo|Precure Twinkle Sound|\u30d7\u30ea\u30ad\u30e5\u30a2\u2606\u30c8\u30a5\u30a4\u30f3\u30af\u30eb\u2606\u30b5\u30a6\u30f3\u30c9\u2606\u5f61}}, was released by Marvelous on May 29, 2019 with songs taken from the first half of the anime including the transformation theme {{nihongo|\"Star Color Pendant! Color Charge!\"|\u30b9\u30bf\u30fc\u30ab\u30e9\u30fc\u30da\u30f3\u30c0\u30f3\u30c8! \u30ab\u30e9\u30fc\u30c1\u30e3\u30fc\u30b8\uff01}} performed by the main cast. The second official soundtrack, titled {{nihongo|Precure Sound Imagination!!|\u30d7\u30ea\u30ad\u30e5\u30a2\u2606\u30b5\u30a6\u30f3\u30c9\u2606\u30a4\u30de\u30b8\u30cd\u30fc\u30b7\u30e7\u30f3!!}}, was released on December 18, 2019 with songs taken from the second half. In addition, a vocal best album was released on January 22, 2020 with fourteen songs taken from the anime and its movie including Twinkle Stars, Papepipu\u2606Romantic, and a special version of the transformation theme from episode 48.\n\n===Music===\n\n==== Opening ====\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!Song\n!Artist\n!Episodes\n|-\n|{{nihongo|'''\"Sparkle\u2606\u5f61Star\u2606Twinkle PreCure\"'''|\u30ad\u30e9\u30ea\u2606\u5f61\u30b9\u30bf\u30fc\u2606\u30c8\u30a5\u30a4\u30f3\u30af\u30eb\u30d7\u30ea\u30ad\u30e5\u30a2}}\n|Rie Kitagawa\n|All\n|}\n\n==== Endings ====\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Song\n!Artist\n!Episodes\n|-\n|{{nihongo|'''\"Papepipu\u2606Romantic\"'''|\u30d1\u307a\u30d4\u30d7\u2606\u30ed\u30de\u30f3\u30c1\u30c3\u30af}}\n|rowspan=2|[[Chihaya Yoshitake]]\n|1 - 5,